<DOCNO> XIE19971208.0002 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> British NFU Leader Urges Farmers to End Blockade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, December 7 (Xinhua) -- A leader of the British National
Farmers Union (NFU) today appealed to British farmers to put an
end to their blockade across the country in protest against cheap
beef imports.
</P>
<P>
NFU President David Naish made the appeal early today when the
farmers' protests are quickly spreading across the whole country
and thousands of farmers were set to turn up at ports like
Stranraer, Dover, Liverpool and Plymouth.
</P>
<P>
Naish was quoted by the BBC television as saying, "I am asking
them (farmers) not to block the roads. The dispute is with the
government, not with the public and not with the shops and not
with anybody else."
</P>
<P>
The farmers' leader also made it clear that it was important
that people should not be inconvenienced and otherwise they might
lose sympathy.
</P>
<P>
"I very much hope therefore that the farmers don't
inconvenience the public -- we need the general public on our
side," he added.
</P>
<P>
British farmers were further angered Wednesday when British
Agriculture Minister Jack Cunningham proposed a ban on beef sold
on the bone to prevent a possible risk of infecting with the mad
cow disease. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
