<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe's Army Told to Take Professional Courses </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, December 7 (Xinhua) -- Members of the Zimbabwe
National Army have been urged to take advantage of the peace
prevailing in the region and pursue non military professional
courses to enhance their lifestyles.
</P>
<P>
Deputy Minister of Higher Education Sikhanyiso Ndlovu today
told a function named "Band Sunday" for the army in Bulawayo, the
country's second largest city that military courses would help
them to start and improve their own income generating projects
when they leave the army.
</P>
<P>
"Educating the military establishment is a force freeing the
individual and the nation from the bondage of ignorance, poverty,
insecurity and incapability," he said.
</P>
<P>
He added, "you must therefore be prepared educationally in
matters pertaining to the needs of society, the national and the
international community in order for you to make better
decisions."
</P>
<P>
Band Sunday is an occasion during which the army interacts
with suppliers of its goods and services from various sectors of
the economy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
