<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Britain Hopeful of Kyoto Deal Despite Difficulties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, December 7 (Xinhua) -- British Deputy Prime Minister
John Prescott today expressed Britain's optimism about striking a
deal on reducing gas emissions despite serious differences among
various participants at the UN climate talks in Kyoto, Japan.
</P>
<P>
Prescott was quoted by the BBC television as saying in Kyoto
today that the climate conference was split over concrete
reductions of the greenouse gas emissions, but he still thought
"there is political will for an agreement now."
</P>
<P>
"If we don't get an agreement, then quite frankly it will be
quite catastrophic," he said.
</P>
<P>
The deputy prime minister sounded an optimistic tune by saying,
"I think no one wants to be blamed for the breakdown of this
conference because public opinion is such that they want to see an
agreement on the environment."
</P>
<P>
It was reported that the United States, the world's biggest
polluter, wants to stabilize gas emissions at 1990 levels between
2008 and 2012, while the European Union demands a 15 percent cut
on 1990 levels by 2012. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
