<HEADLINE> US Changes Strategy on Nuclear Arms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 7 (Xinhua) -- US President Bill Clinton
has issued new guidelines for the use of nuclear weapons, ordering
the Pentagon to shift the focus from planning a prolonged nuclear
fight with a superpower to deterring chemical or biological attacks
from maller powers.
</P>
<P>
The president's new orders were issued last month to the
secretary of defense and chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff,
The Washington Post reported today citing senior administration
officials.
</P>
<P>
The guidelines replace those that were put in place in 1981
under President Reagan at the height of the cold war as Clinton
realized that much of the old policy was outdated.
</P>
<P>
The new guidelines, signed by Clinton just before Thanksgiving,
recognize the world's fundamental shift in power and the rapidly
changing threats to the United States since the collapse of the
Soviet Union.
</P>
<P>
The guidelines ordered the Pentagon to revise its strategy to
win an all-out nuclear war with the Soviet Union. Instead, the
Pentagon must be prepared to use the United States' still
formidable nuclear weapons to respond swiftly and decisively to
more limited attacks.
</P>
<P>
Clinton's action marks the first formal adjustment in 16 years
of presidential policy for the targeting of US nuclear weapons and
could pave the way for further reductions in the total number of
such weapons, senior officials were quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
But in many ways, the guidelines do not change the posture of
the United States' nuclear forces, which include air, land and
submarine-launched missiles and affirm that the United States will
continue to rely on nuclear arms as a cornerstone of its national
security for the indefinite future, said Robert G. Bell, a special
assistant to the president. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971208.0010 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nepali Coalition Govt Vows to Ensure Law and Order </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, December 7 (Xinhua) -- Nepal's present coalition
government is determined to ensure law and order in the country
and will launch a public security drive to free the country from
killings and terror, said a document titled "joint policy and
programs" issued today by the ruling partners.
</P>
<P>
The coalition government has decided to come up with a concrete
program within one month on the basis of a national consensus
among responsible political parties, said the 21-point document
issued by the National Democratic Party (RPP), the Nepali Congress
(NC) and the Nepal Sadbhavana Party.
</P>
<P>
The police and the administration will be effectively mobilized
to end the violence by the ultra-leftist guerrillas under the name
of people's war, the document said.
</P>
<P>
More than 100 people including policemen, civilians, government
officials have been killed since February 1996 when the guerrillas
launched their movement in the mid-western part of the country.
</P>
<P>
The NC had accused the former coalition government of being
ineffective in dealing with the guerrillas.
</P>
<P>
The three coalition partners said they would also resolve the
Bhutanese refugee problem with the cooperation of India.
</P>
<P>
About 100,000 Bhutanese refugees have been staying in eastern
Nepal in eight UN-run camps after being forced to flee Bhutan in
1989 and early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
Nepal and Bhutan have held seven rounds of ministerial-level
talks on the issue but reached no agreement.
</P>
<P>
Nepal has asked India, who handles Bhutan's foreign and defense
affairs, to help resolve the problem, but India refused, saying it
is a bilateral issue.
</P>
<P>
The document said the coalition government will also
immediately launch a program for promoting economic activities by
taking the private sector into confidence.
</P>
<P>
The NC, which toppled the former coalition government in early
October with a no-confidence motion, joined the RPP-led coalition
government on December 3.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971208.0011 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Everything Is Now Perfectly Normal in Zambia, </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, December 7 (Xinhua) -- Zambian President Fredrick
Chiluba said here today that "everything is now perfectly normal
in Zambia after the October 28 coup attempt and as you can see
our region is peaceful at the moment."
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters after a two-hour meeting with Zimbabwean
President Robert Mugabe, Chiluba said he discussed with President
Mugabe all matters affecting the region.
</P>
<P>
Chiluba was in the country to brief Mugabe, in his capacity as
chairman of the Organisation of African Unity (OAU) and the
Southern African Development Community (SADC) organ on politics,
defence and security, on the recent foiled coup attempt that was
staged by junior army officers in his country.
</P>
<P>
Chiluba said, "i live in the embarrassment that unlike most
African countries i have no-one to look up to as the founding
father of the Zambian nation, i'm embarrassed because i was
robbed of that pride."
</P>
<P>
"We hope and trust that some day my older brother (Kaunda)
will wake up and realise that his time in politics is up and
leave the country to grow peacefully and economically but i
haven't pinched him, not at all," Chiluba said.
</P>
<P>
He also said, "Zambia will not reverse its current political
path, economic reform programmes and other essential policies
that are directly related to the democratic progress."
</P>
<P>
He said Zambia would not abandon the privatisation programme
despite an outcry by individuals against reforms.
</P>
<P>
On the reported Zambia-Angola strained relations over the
failed coup attempt, Chiluba said, "our relations have never been
strained, there have been rumours and speculations in the press,
i'm being honest with you, there are no problems between Zambia
and Angola."
</P>
<P>
Chiluba arrived in the country this morning for the one-day visit.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
