<BODY>
<HEADLINE> SADC to Settle Differences On Security Organ: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, December 7 (Xinhua) -- Southern African Development
Community (SADC) countries will soon meet to discuss and settle
the differences over the organization's organ on politics,
defense and security.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwean President Robert Mugabe, the current SADC chairman,
said here today after a meeting with Zambian President Frederick
Chiluba, SADC member countries had agreed during their last
September summit in Blantyre, Malawi, that they should resolve
the issue amicably to ensure the issue would not bring any
hostilities between member countries.
</P>
<P>
The organ on politics, defense and security is an off shoot of
the now defunct frontline states which fought apartheid South
Africa which attained independence in 1994.
</P>
<P>
Now current SADC Chairman, President Nelson Mandala has
demanded that the organ be answerable to the regional grouping
rather than remain a separate entity, which Zimbabwe and at least
three other countries have resisted.
</P>
<P>
"Differences in perceptions do arise but we must all guard
gainst them so that we do not allow them to split our
organization. We have to work them out and move together
positively," Mugabe said.
</P>
<P>
"That is South Africa's view point that the organ must not
operate as a separate establishment altogether for the SADC
region," he said.
</P>
<P>
"The view for the organ to operate as a separate establishment
was accepted by the majority of the SADC countries and it was
upon the need to sign the protocol that South Africa's view point
was made in a manner which has now caused us to look at the organ
again," Mugabe said.
</P>
<P>
Mugabe added that South Africa may not be alone in its view
point and the meeting, whose venue and date has still to be made
public, sought to settle the differences and perceptions
amicably.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971208.0014 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ousted S. Leone President Takes Money Printer to </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FREETOWN, December 7 (Xinhua)-- Ousted Sierra Leone leader
Tejan Kabbah disclosed Friday that his deposed government has
taken the London-based currency printing firm of Thomas de la Rue
to court "to block disbursement of state funds" to the military
junta in Sierra Leone.
</P>
<P>
The firm of de la Rue has been the sole printer of all Sierra
Leone currency since independence in 1961.
</P>
<P>
Kabbah said to the clandestine FM 98.1 radio that the junta in
Sierra Leone wanted to withdraw some money left in the de la
Rue's account of Sierra Leone.
</P>
<P>
"I was advised by the British government that any action
against the company would only be effective if an injunction is
brought on the company in a British Court,' Kabbah declared.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Government Spokesman Allicu Kamara said in spite of
the Conakry Peace Agreement, ousted president Kabbah has
continued to wage a diplomatic war against the military
government.
</P>
<P>
He explained that following the signing of the agreement, the
government applied to the United States Federal Reserve Bank in
America for permission so that the Bank of Sierra Leone could
have access to money and property to do business for the
government abroad.
</P>
<P>
"Apparently, the American authorities contacted Kabbah for the
matter. After the consultation, the Reserve Bank sent a message
to the Sierra Leone government saying that the American
government only recognizes Kabbah as president of Sierra Leone.
</P>
<P>
"The telex message said that Kabbah had instructed that the
Bank of Sierra Leone should not be allowed to do any business
with the reserve Bank or be allowed to draw any money for Sierra
Leone," Kamara said.
</P>
<P>
Kabbah also instructed that any request for such facilities by
the government or the Bank of Sierra Leone should be ignored.
</P>
<P>
The United States government earlier denied it was directly
involved in the matter when the claim was first made last Monday
by the Secretary-general of the military government, Colonel
Abdul Sesay at a press briefing.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
