<BODY>
<HEADLINE> European Business to Face Massive Bill for Converting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, December 7 (Xinhua) -- European businesses could face a
really massive bill for converting to the European single currency
named euro, according to a research report.
</P>
<P>
The survey, prepared by the KPMG Management Consulting, said
that larger European businesses would have to spend more than 30
billion pounds (about 50 billion US dollars) in converting to the
European Monetary Union (EMU).
</P>
<P>
Each major European company would spend an average of 19
million pounds (about 32 million dollars) in this process, said
the survey, which was carried in today's Sunday Times.
</P>
<P>
Vick Pryce, chief economist at KPMG, said, "If the predictions
in this research are accurate, EMU is going to represent a heavy
cost for European business and significant number of companies
will not be ready in time."
</P>
<P>
"We surveyed Europe's largest companies because they have been
the most committed supporters of monetary union. Companies of this
size to be underprepared for the euro could therefore pose
considerable problems in the post-EMU environment," Pryce said.
</P>
<P>
The survey also suggested that larger British companies are
well-advanced in their preparations in spite of the London
government's decision not to join the single currency, due to be
launched in 1999, over the next five years.
</P>
<P>
More than nine out of 10 British firms have carried out a
review of the likely effects of EMU in comparison with 74 percent
of German businesses and 66 percent of Italian firms, the report
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
