<HEADLINE> Russia Denies Promising Unilateral Cuts in Missiles </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, December 7 (Xinhua) -- Russian Defense Minister Igor
Sergeyev has confirmed that President Boris Yeltsin's statement
made in Stockholm means that Russia is ready to cut down its
northwestern military grouping by 40 percent, the Interfax news
service reported today.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with the TV program Vremya Saturday, Sergeyev
said that cuts are to be made in the Kaliningrad special defense
region, in the Leningrad military district and in the Baltic and
Northern fleets.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on Yeltsin's proposal to reduce the number of
nuclear warheads, the minister said the proposal deals with
"further and more radical cuts in the strategic forces within the
limits of the negotiating process."
</P>
<P>
"There was no talk about any unilateral cuts," he noted.
</P>
<P>
Sergeyev indicated this initiative will be implemented if the
Russian Duma ratifies the START-2 treaty, "after which a
transitional period at the START-3 level will begin, with more
radical cuts."
</P>
<P>
Thus, he said, Russia and the United States approaching the
level of strategic armaments will have every right to invite other
members of the nuclear club -- Britain, France and China -- to
join the talks on further cuts with more rigorous control over the
nonproliferation of nuclear know-how.
</P>
<P>
President Boris Yeltsin last Wednesday in Sweden pledged to
unilaterally slash Russia's military presence by more than 40
percent near the Baltics. His remark drew great attention from the
West and the Baltic states. 
</P>
</TEXT>
