<HEADLINE> Iraq Rejects CIA Allegations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, December 7 (Xinhua)-- Iraq today rejected allegations
of the U.S. Central Intelligence Agency (CIA) that Iraq can
produce weapons of mass destruction and long-range missiles again
if without U.N. inspections and restrictions.
</P>
<P>
The official Iraqi News Agency (INA) quoted an Iraqi National
Monitoring Department spokesman as saying that CIA's claims
clearly reveal the ties between U.S. espionage and
U.S. interventions in the work of the U.N. Special Commission
(UNSCOM) on dismantling Iraq's weapons of mass destruction.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman termed the CIA as the only source of the
"misleading statements the U.S. officials and UNSCOM executive
chairman have been making for a month."
</P>
<P>
"CIA is also based on one of its informed sources, UNSCOM,
through which the Americans are leading and steering its anti-Iraq
activities," the spokesman added.
</P>
<P>
Baghdad announced to oust U.S. members of the U.N. inspection
teams last month in charge of espionage, triggering off a crisis
in which Washington threatened military action. Tensions have been
reduced after Russian mediation.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Major General Hossam Mohammed Amin, director general
of Iraq's National Surveillance Department (the Iraqi counterpart
of the UNSCOM) announced that the inspection teams today inspected
18 Iraqi sites of the industry, water supply and sewerage sectors
in addition to a site in a university.
</P>
<P>
The teams also visited a customs complex situated on the Iraqi-
Turkish border.
</P>
<P>
Amin said that the Iraqi side cooperated completely with the
UNSCOM teams and provided for them the support required.
</P>
<P>
It is the 16th day for the UNSCOM teams to resume their duties
in Iraq since Iraq decided to allow U.S. members of the UNSCOM
arms inspection teams to take part in arms inspections. 
</P>
</TEXT>
