<HEADLINE> Netanyahu Briefs Inner Cabinet on European Visit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, December 7 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu today briefed the inner cabinet members on his
just-concluded talks with European leaders and U.S. Secretary of
State Madeleine Albright on advancing the peace process.
</P>
<P>
The inner cabinet meeting was convened Sunday afternoon shortly
after Netanyahu returned from Paris after his talks with Albright,
German Chancellor Helmut Kohl and French President Jacques Chirac.
</P>
<P>
During his two meetings with Albright in Paris, Netanyahu was
asked to make a "more credible" decision on the further
redeployment as soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
On Saturday, Albright held a meeting with Palestinian National
Authority (PNA) President Yasser Arafat in Geneva, Switzerland,
in a bid to narrow the gap between Israel and the PNA over the
further troop redeployments. To balance her pressure on Israel on
the redeployment issue, she demanded Arafat launch an all-out war
against terrorism.
</P>
<P>
Today's meeting, attended by Israeli Foreign Minister David
Levy, Defense Minister Yitzhak Mordechai and National
Infrastructure Minister Ariel Sharon, also discussed the planned
second phase of Israeli troop redeployment in the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
It was the third session held by the four-member inner cabinet
which was formed to decide the extent of further redeployment and
the guidelines on the permanent talks with the PNA.
</P>
<P>
The cabinet has yet to overcome the different approaches among
the ministers on Israel's security needs, including the size of
the proposed security zones to be discussed in the final-status
talks.
</P>
<P>
Albright is due to hold another round of talks separately with
Netanyahu and Arafat in Europe next week in further peace effort.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu said Friday it would take several weeks for his inner
cabinet to formulate the extent of further redeployment as well as
the guidelines on the permanent talks. 
</P>
