<HEADLINE> Russian Premier: Too Early to Say Reasons of Aircrash </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, December 7 (Xinhua) -- Head of the Russian government
Viktor Chernomyrdin arrived in Irkutsk early this morning for the
investigation work on the air crash which created serious damage
in the resident region, according to the Itar-Tass news agency.
</P>
<P>
Chernomyrdin told reporters that work on overcoming
consequences of the tragedy proceeds promptly and in an organized
manner.
</P>
<P>
He said it is too early to speak about reasons for the tragedy.
"We should not draw hasty conclusions," he added.
</P>
<P>
According to Chernomyrdin, a government decision will be signed
today to allocate funds and to render relief aid to the victims.
Funds will be channeled to build a new children's home and 72
flats for those who were deprived of housing. Some 50 billion
roubles (8.45 million US dollars) will be appropriated for these
purposes.
</P>
<P>
A representative of the Russian Ministry for Emergencies in
Moscow was quoted as saying that bodies of 41 people were found at
the site of the air crash by 12:00 Moscow time. The fate of
supposedly 23 people remains unknown. Fifteen people, including
seven children, were hospitalized.
</P>
<P>
The military cargo plane, An-124 Ruslan, took off from the
factory airfield in Irkutsk at 09:45 Moscow time Saturday and
plummeted on a housing neighborhood several seconds after the
take-off from an altitude of 70 meters and burst into flames.
</P>
<P>
The plane destroyed one 64-flat four-storeyed house, damaged
one 100-flat five-storeyed house, two 16-flat wooden houses, the
three-storeyed building of a school and the four-storeyed building
of a children's home. 
</P>
</TEXT>
