<HEADLINE> Backgrounder: Chronology of Islamic Summits </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, December 7 (Xinhua) -- The following is a chronology of
the summits of the Organization of the Islamic Conference:
</P>
<P>
-- The first Islamic summit was held in Rabat, capital of
Morocco, on September 22-25, 1969 with the participation of 25
heads of state, to recommend the establishment of the
Organization of the Islamic Conference (OIC). In March 1970
Islamic foreign ministers met for the first time to translate the
proposal into reality. The OIC was formed in the following May in
Jeddah, Saudi Arabia with the aim of promoting Islamic solidarity
and cooperation.
</P>
<P>
-- The second Islamic summit was held in the Pakistani city of
Lahore on February 22-24, 1974 with the participation of heads of
states and representatives from 36 Muslim countries. The summit
decided to offer assistance to Egypt, Syria, Jordan and the
Palestinian people against Israeli occupation.
</P>
<P>
-- The third Islamic summit was held in Mecca and Taif, Saudi
Arabia on January 25-29, 1981 with the participation of 38 Muslim
countries and decided that summit conference would be held every
three years in future. The summit reaffirmed earlier resolutions
on the liberation of all Arab and Palestinian territories under
Israeli occupation, and assignation of Jerusalem as the capital of
a Palestinian state.
</P>
<P>
-- The fourth Islamic summit was held in Casablanca, Morocco on
January 16-19, 1984 with the participation of 42 Muslim
countries. It called for Israeli withdrawal from all Arab and
Palestinian territories it captured in 1967.
</P>
<P>
-- The fifth Islamic summit was held in Kuwait on January 26-
29, 1987 with the participation of 44 Muslim countries. It
emphasized the Palestinian issue was the core of Arab-Israeli
conflict and there can be no just and lasting peace without a
complete and unconditional Israeli withdrawal from all occupied
territories.
</P>
<P>
-- The sixth Islamic summit was held in Dakar, capital of
Senegal on December 9-11, 1991 with the participation of 45
Muslim countries. Iraq boycotted the summit, which condemned the
Iraqi invasion of Kuwait and voiced support for effort toward
a just and lasting peace in the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
-- The seventh Islamic summit was held in Casablanca, Morocco
on December 13-15, 1994 with the participation of 54 Muslim
countries. It demanded the return of all Israeli-occupied Arab
lands and realization of a complete peace in the Middle East based
on U.N. resolutions. It condemned the Serbs' brutality against
Muslims in Bosnia-Herzegovina.
</P>
<P>
-- The eighth Islamic summit is to be held on December 9-11 in
Tehran, Iran with an anticipated participation of 54 countries. It
is expected to endorse more than 140 resolutions in various fields
and discuss the formation of an Islamic common market. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971208.0024 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Bank Helps Lagos With Tap Water </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, December 7 (Xinhua) -- More people in Lagos, the
largest city and economic center of Nigeria, are expected to
enjoy tap water with the completion of a World Bank-assisted
water project this month.
</P>
<P>
The 173-million-U.S. Dollar project has helped lay 800 km of
water pipes with a capacity to serve 60 percent of the local
people, the News Agency of Nigeria reported today, quoting the
general manager of Lagos State Water Corporation.
</P>
<P>
Part of the project also covers the rehabilitation of the
corporation's largest Iju waterworks, which is expected to supply
45 million gallons of water per day.
</P>
<P>
In a report issued a week ago, the corporation, the sole water
supplier in the country, said the current water supply stands at
827 million liters a day, which can meet only 40 percent of
demand.
</P>
<P>
The demand for tap water is expected to rise to 1,509 million
cubic liters per day by the year 2010 with population projected
to be 12.4 million at that time, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The report attributes the short supply to financial
constraints in the state government and calls for the
participation of private investors to meet and sustain the water
needs of the people.
</P>
<P>
Lagos is one of the largest metropolises in Africa, which has
a population of about 10 million and covers an area of 3,577
square kilometers with 22 percent of lagoons and creeks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
