<HEADLINE> Israel's Nationwide Strike Expected to Be Over Soon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, December 7 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Trade Union is
expected to sign a compromise agreement with Finance Ministry
this evening to end the five-day nationwide strike, Israel Radio
reported today.
</P>
<P>
The breakthrough came late this afternoon when the National
Labor Court succeeded in brokering a compromise, which was
accepted by both the Trade Union Chairman Amir Peretz and Finance
Minister Yaakov Neeman.
</P>
<P>
At a news briefing, Peretz said the understanding has nearly
resolved all of the sticking points related to the strike, which
was launched last Wednesday in protest against government plans
for wages reform and privatization.
</P>
<P>
He said that the Treasury has made significant compromises,
noting that if both sides sign an agreement on principles this
evening, he will announce an end to the strike.
</P>
<P>
Neeman said he has accepted the court's proposal and hoped for
an early end to the conflict.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that the strike has caused irreversible damage to
the country's economy.
</P>
<P>
As the strike by 700,000 public sector employees entered its
fifth day today, the situation in the country became almost
intolerable, especially in the airports, where hundreds of
passengers were stranded.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Manufacturer Association estimated that the economic
losses caused by the strike is approaching 200 million shekels
(about 57 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
The strike is the latest round in a Trade Union battle against
the government's economic reform plans, which have sparked fears
that worker's rights would be harmed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
