<HEADLINE> Israeli Trade Union Announces End to Nationwide </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, December 7 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Trade Union today
announced an end to the crippling five-day nationwide strike,
saying that the striking workers will return to their work
tonight, Israel Channel 1 Television reported.
</P>
<P>
The breakthrough came late this afternoon when the National
Labor Court succeeded in brokering a compromise, which was
accepted by both the Trade Union Chairman Amir Peretz and Finance
Minister Yaakov Neeman.
</P>
<P>
Representatives of the Trade Union and the Treasury are
working out a memorandum of understanding to settle the dispute
over the wages reform.
</P>
<P>
The strike, which was attended by 700,000 public sector
employees, was launched last Wednesday in protest against
government's plans for wages reform and privatization.
</P>
<P>
It has paralyzed the country by effectively shutting down
airports, seaports, banks, the Tel Aviv Stock Exchange, government
offices and state-owned industries.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Manufacturer Association estimated that the economic
losses caused by the strike are around 200 million shekels (about
57 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
The strike was triggered by the remarks made by Neeman on
December 1 that striking workers were "exploding bombs" and
enemies from within. About 150,000 workers had been on a two-day
strike starting from November 30.
</P>
<P>
In response to the assault, Peretz declared the strike last
Tuesday night at an emergency gathering of thousands of union
members in Tel Aviv.
</P>
<P>
The strike is the latest round in a Trade Union battle against
the government's economic reform plans, which have sparked fears
that workers' rights would be harmed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
