<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-07 20:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> OIC Foreign Ministers' Meeting Ends in Tehran </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, December 7 (Xinhua) -- Foreign ministers of the
Organization of Islamic Conference (OIC) concluded their two-day
session here this evening, paving the way for the 8th OIC summit
to be held on December 9-11.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, the foreign ministers narrowed their
differences on a number of issues, and endorsed more than 140
draft resolutions in the fields of politics, economy and culture.
</P>
<P>
They successfully resolved dispute over relations between
Islamic countries and Israel, and the issue of northern Iraq.
</P>
<P>
The meeting adopted a Syrian proposal that opposed Islamic
countries' military cooperation with the Jewish state, despite
Turkey's reservation.
</P>
<P>
They also reaffirmed full respect for Iraq's sovereignty and
territorial integrity.
</P>
<P>
But informed sources said that Iran was against a Syrian
recommendation to condemn Turkey's incursions into northern Iraq
for fear of implicating itself, thus angering Damascus.
</P>
<P>
Tehran is reportedly supporting a Kurdish faction in fighting
for control of northern Iraq.
</P>
<P>
The reservations of OIC members toward a variety of resolutions
did not prevent the meeting from working out a draft agenda and
program for the summit.
</P>
<P>
It also recommended that the summit be entitled "session of
dignity, dialog and participation."
</P>
<P>
It decided to grant observer status to the Republic of Cote
d'Ivoire of west Africa.
</P>
<P>
Altogether 49 foreign ministers and deputy foreign ministers,
and representatives of 20-odd international organizations attended
the meeting, the 24th since the founding of the OIC in 1970.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
