<DOCNO> XIE19971208.0030 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-07 20:33 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nurse Tomb of Ancient Egypt's King Unearthed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, December 7 (Xinhua) -- Archaeologists have found the
tomb of the wet nurse of ancient Egyptian King Tutankhamen and
said it is an extremely rare case in which a tomb was devoted to a
single woman thousands of years ago.
</P>
<P>
The tomb, which dates back to 1330 B.C., has been unearthed in
the Sakkara area, 20 kilometers south of Cairo, by a French
archaeological mission, Middle East News Agency quoted Egyptian
Minister of Culture Farouk Hosni as saying.
</P>
<P>
This area was a mausoleum of the courtiers and high-ranking
officials of the New Kingdom of ancient Egypt from 1400 B.C. to
1100 B.C..
</P>
<P>
One scene on the walls of the tomb featured the nurse, whom has
been identified as Maya, with the six-year-old king sitting in her
lap.
</P>
<P>
But archaeologists did not find any gold, funerary objects, or
Maya's coffin in the tomb.
</P>
<P>
The French team has cleared two of the five known chambers. A
third was filled with rubble, and two others were sealed off with
masonry.
</P>
<P>
The excavation was expected to finish in two years.
</P>
<P>
The discovery of Maya's tomb coincided with the 75th
anniversary of that of Tutankhamen's, which was kept intact when
it was uncovered by British archaeologist Howard Carter in the
Valley of Kings near Luxor, about 500 kilometers south of Cairo.
</P>
<P>
Tutankhamen, who died at 19 in a suspected palace coup, was
believed to be the youngest pharaoh of ancient Egypt. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
