<HEADLINE> Zambian Ruling Party Seeks Talks With Opposition </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, December 7 (Xinhua) -- Zambia's ruling Movement for
Multi-party Democracy (MMD) will set an office in the capital
city of Lusaka Monday where the opposition parties interested in
dialogues with the ruling party can register.
</P>
<P>
MMD national secretary Micheal Sata said here today that the
preliminary meeting of the inter-party dialogues will start
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
He said the ruling party will not set any pre-conditions for
the inter-party talks.
</P>
<P>
The inter-party talks failed to kick off as planned in last
July after opposition parties renewed their calls for abolishing
the current constitution, establishing an interim government and
new elections.
</P>
<P>
But now the United National Independent Party (UNIP) has said
it is ready to attend the inter-party talks without setting out
pre-conditions.
</P>
<P>
UNIP chairman Malimba Masheke told a news conference last
Thursday that his party is willing to attend the talks regardless
of who chairs the meeting but only as long as the contentious
national issues are included on the agenda.
</P>
<P>
He said the issue of dialogue is now becoming monotonous and
hoped the meeting of party secretary generals scheduled to take
place ahead of the inter-party talks would set out an agenda that
will address the issues causing the political impasse in the
country.  
</P>
