<HEADLINE> Peter Musonge Re-Appointed as Cameroon's PM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YAOUNDE, December 7 (Xinhua) -- Cameroon's Prime Minister
Peter Mafany Musonge was re-appointed Sunday as the Prime
Minister of the Republic of Cameroon at the same time the
government was dismissed, said Radio Cameroon this evening.
</P>
<P>
According to the press release signed here today by Amadou
Ali, the Secretary General at the presidency, the appointment was
contained in a presidential decree after the meeting of the
ministerial council presided over by President Paul Biya here
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The reorganization of the government was also contained in
another presidential decree which was signed on the same day.
</P>
<P>
Peter Mafany Musonge, 45, the former General Director of the
Cameroon Development Corporation -- one of the largest
state-owned agro-industrial companies in the country, was firstly
appointed as the prime minister on November 19, 1996.
</P>
<P>
Since November 3, when President Biya took oath for his new
term as president of the country, Cameroonians have been waiting
for the formation of a new government.
</P>
<P>
At today's ministerial council's meeting, Biya extended his
congratulations to the team for the continuous support giving to
him during the just ended five-year mandate.
</P>
<P>
According to the presidential decree, there will be 28
ministries in the new government. But the name list of the new
ministers at the press time remains unannounced. 
</P>
</TEXT>
