<HEADLINE> Turkish Military Operation Continues in Northern </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, December 7 (Xinhua) -- Turkey's cross-border military
operation in northern Iraq entered the third day today, dealing a
heavy blow on the outlawed Kurdish Workers' Party (PKK).
</P>
<P>
Two F-16 jets of the Turkish Air Force bombed the PKK
positions in Khwakurk near the Iranian border as the Turkish
ground troops continued their battle, the Anatolia News Agency
quoted military sources as saying.
</P>
<P>
Some 20 PKK rebels were reportedly killed in Sunday fighting
with the government troops. No casualties of the government
soldiers were available.
</P>
<P>
The latest military operation started last Friday when around
20,000 Turkish government troops poured across the border to round
up some 1,000 PKK militants who gathered in Khwakurk for the past
weeks.
</P>
<P>
Iraqi Foreign Ministry Saturday issued a statement condemning
Turkey's invasion of the Iraqi sovereignty and territorial
integrity, demanding an immediate pull-out of the Turkish troops.
</P>
<P>
Turkey has repeatedly launched cross-border incursions to wipe
out the PKK camps in norther Iraq, leading to strong protests
from Iran and the Arab countries.
</P>
<P>
Baghdad has lost its effective control over northern Iraq
since its defeat by the Western alliance in the 1991 Gulf War
following the Iraqi invasion of Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
The PKK has been fighting a 13-year-old separatist war for
autonomy in eastern and southeastern Turkey, which has claimed
over 28,000 lives. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
