<HEADLINE> Financial Instability Continuing in South Korean </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, December 8 (Xinhua) -- Although the first tranche of the
International Monetary Fund (IMF)'s bailout package arrived in
Seoul last Saturday, instability in South Korea's financial sector
was continuing with local currency depreciating and interest rate
soaring.
</P>
<P>
The South Korean won, weakened all the daytime to close at
1,342.40 against one U.S. dollar, hit its daily drop limit of 10
percent the first time since South Korea and the IMF reached an
agreement to bailout its ailing economy.
</P>
<P>
The basic exchange rate to be posted Tuesday will be 1,332.50
won against one U.S. dollar, a 112.10 won lower from Monday's.
</P>
<P>
Although the IMF sent its first installment of the rescue loan
amounting 5.2 billion dollars to Seoul over last weekend, many
investors felt that the loan would hardly satisfy the fund
shortage hitting the local financial and business sectors.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the yield for guaranteed three-year corporate bonds
soared to a historic high of 22.95 percent, along with annual
yields on call loans reaching 25 percent.
</P>
<P>
Reflecting the wide-spreading fears that current fund shortage
in both company and financial sector is likely to worsen, the
composite stock price index on Monday plunged 20.9 points to close
at 414.83 points. 
</P>
</TEXT>
