<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Penglai Port Opens to World </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANTAI, December 8 (Xinhua) -- Penglai, a category-1 port on
Shandong Peninsula in east China, entered operations today.
</P>
<P>
The port, one of four major ports in ancient China, was an
important harbor facilitating sea transportation with Japan and
Korea.
</P>
<P>
An eight year construction effort transformed Penglai into a
category-1 port open for year-round navigation.
</P>
<P>
The port consists of two harbor areas, with the western area
ranking as one of the province's major harbors in terms of
business volume. The area features four 1,000-dwt and five 500-dwt
berths for passenger ships, two 500-dwt berths for commodities,
and one 100-dwt dock for landing.
</P>
<P>
The eastern area features three harbors rated at 10,000-dwt,
5,000-dwt and 2,000-dwt berths respectively, with the total annual
handling capacity for the three standing at 1.2 million tons.
</P>
<P>
In addition to a 15,200 sq.m. storage yard and warehouses, the
port is also equipped with complete facilities for port
operations, navigation and telecommunications, as well as
facilities for water and power supply.
</P>
<P>
Opening of the port is expected to add great impetus to local
economic development.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971208.0040 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Singapore Sets Up Committees on Financial Reform </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, December 8 (Xinhua) -- The Singapore government has
set up three committees to review regulation of the local stock
market, the corporate financing sector and rules over disclosure
of information by banks, the Prime Minister's Office announced
here today.
</P>
<P>
It said that the Financial Sector Review Group, chaired by
Deputy Prime Minister Lee Hsien Loong, has formed two committees
to study issues related to Singapore's capital markets.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the Financial Sector Review Group has also set up
another committee to study commercial banking disclosure
standards.
</P>
<P>
The committees would aim to develop Singapore's role as a
financial center by providing scope for initiative and innovation
while keeping the integrity of the system, the Prime Minister's
Office said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
The intention would be to shift the emphasis "from regulation
to supervision" and focus more on systemic risks than on
protecting individual participants, products or projects, it said.
</P>
<P>
The committee on the Stock Exchange of Singapore (SES) Review
would consider regulatory and structural options and recommend a
conceptual framework that will make Singapore's capital markets
more international, competitive and robust, and able to
participate fully in the dynamic global network of capital
markets.
</P>
<P>
"This includes liberalizing market access and commission rates
for transaction," it said.
</P>
<P>
The committee will also review the regulations, by-laws,
administrative notices and other prudential and regulatory
approaches of the SES, and recommend industry development
initiatives by the government, the SES, and member firms of the
SES.
</P>
<P>
The Committee on Corporate Financing Issues will recommend an
appropriate framework of rules, regulations and administrative
guidelines governing corporate fund-raising that will support
steady and sustainable growth of corporations in Singapore, foster
innovation and entrepreneurship, and make Singapore an attractive
center for international corporate fund-raising activities.
</P>
<P>
It will also recommend ways to improve the efficiency of the
fund-raising process, as well as standards of corporate
disclosure.
</P>
<P>
The committee on banking disclosure standards will review and
evaluate banking disclosure standards and practices in the
developed and the Asia-Pacific countries, and to recommend changes
in disclosure standards and practices for Singapore banks, with a
view to attaining the standards of disclosure of the developed
countries.
</P>
<P>
The Prime Minister's Office said that the principles outlined
by the government for these committees also included providing
greater transparency in regulations, and relying more on market
discipline and full information disclosure to protect investors.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
