<HEADLINE> Serbians to Vote Twice for New President </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, December 8 (Xinhua) -- Serbian voters will have to
cast their ballots for the second time to elect a new president
for the republic.
</P>
<P>
The run-up election, as called for by the procedure, is
announced Monday and scheduled for December 21.
</P>
<P>
Racing into the new round will be the top two of the three
candidates in Sunday's election, when none of them gained half of
the votes cast.
</P>
<P>
They are Serbian Foreign Minister Milan Milutinovic, of
Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic's ruling Socialist Party,
and Vojislav Seselj, of the Radical Party.
</P>
<P>
In the first round, joined by some 51 percent of the 7.2
million eligible electorate, Milutinovic pocketed about 43 percent
of the votes compared with Seselj's 32.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
Although a straight majority will be sufficient in the second
round for deciding the president-elect, the voter turnout must
exceed 50 percent of the electorate for a valid result.
</P>
<P>
Seselj defeated Socialist candidate Zoran Lilic in a
presidential poll in October but the vote was below the 50 percent
threshold for his election. 
</P>
</TEXT>
