<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Seminar Marks 60th Anniversary of Nanjing Massacre </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANJING, December 8 (Xinhua) -- Historians in east China's
Jiangsu Province gathered today in Nanjing, the provincial
capital, to attend a seminar marking the 60th anniversary of
Nanjing Massacre.
</P>
<P>
Over the past 60 years, historians in the province have
extended great effort to collect volumes of historical documents
and to systematically study the Nanjing Massacre. Provincial
historians have earned an excellent reputation in the field of
international history.
</P>
<P>
Historians noted that Japanese aggressors launched an invasion
in Shanghai on August 13, 1937, and seized Nanjing, the Chinese
capital at that time, on December 13.
</P>
<P>
Some 300,000 Chinese civilians and unarmed soldiers were
savagely butchered and almost a third of the city's houses were
destroyed.
</P>
<P>
The historians pointed out that the Chinese people will never
forget the tragedy and cannot accept the fact that some Japanese
continue to distort the truth.
</P>
<P>
They expressed the hope that the Japanese Government will
respect the fact and convince the Chinese and Asian peoples that
Japan will never again resort to aggression. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
