<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zhu Pledges No Devaluation of Chinese RMB </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 8 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Vice-Premier Zhu Rongji
said today that the Renminbi (RMB), the Chinese currency, will not
be devalued.
</P>
<P>
Zhu made the remark during a meeting with Lee Kuan Yew, senior
minister of the Prime Minister's Office of Singapore.
</P>
<P>
He said that China views the financial turmoil in southeast and
east Asia regions with all due seriousness, but will not adopt
unnecessary measures to depreciate the RMB.
</P>
<P>
"I can solemnly declare that the Chinese RMB will not be
devalued," Zhu told the Singaporean senior minister.
</P>
<P>
Lee noted that the Chinese economy is on a healthy development
track, with the general situation much better than three to four
years ago. Lee attributed the success to the soft-landing of
China's economy a few years ago.
</P>
<P>
The recent financial crisis in southeast and east Asia has
created a series of problems affecting economic development in the
region, said Lee. However, he expressed his belief that China can
withstand the test and maintain the sustained and healthy
development of economy by adopting continuous readjustments.
</P>
<P>
Zhu briefed Lee on China's economic development, expressing his
optimism about the prospects of China's economic advancement.
</P>
<P>
Zhu noted that China is obviously concerned about financial
turmoil in southeast and east Asia, and is clearly aware of its
present situation.
</P>
<P>
He added that the Chinese government held a financial work
conference recently to analyze the related situation seriously and
adopted necessary measures.
</P>
<P>
Zhu stressed that China will implement necessary measures,
improve the competitiveness of the nation's export products and
extend great efforts to further reduce tariffs in order to provide
more favorable conditions for foreign investors.
</P>
<P>
Dai Xianglong, governor of the People's Bank of China; and Zeng
Peiyan, vice-minister of the State planning Commission; attended
the meeting. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
