<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Scheme to Help Tenants Own Their Own Houses </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, December 8 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong is to introduce a
new housing scheme, under which tenants living in selected public
housing blocks can buy their rental units at prices about one
eighth of the market value.
</P>
<P>
The Housing Authority (HA) today endorsed the Tenants Purchase
Scheme (TPS), under which tenants only need to pay about 12
percent of the assessed market value to own their flats if they
buy in the first year after the scheme is introduced.
</P>
<P>
Rosanna Wong, chairwoman of the HA, said that the scheme would
make a significant contribution to achieving the 70 percent
ownership target set by Chief Executive Tung Chee Hwa in his first
policy address in early October this year.
</P>
<P>
She added: "Purchasers will generally spend no more than twice
of what they currently pay for their rents." About 25,000 units
will be put up for sale in the first phase. Those who buy in the
second year of the introduction of the scheme have to pay 21
percent of market value.
</P>
<P>
Sky-high property prices in Hong Kong have deterred buyers,
posing a tough challenge for the Special Administrative Region
(SAR) government.
</P>
<P>
In his inaugural policy address, Tung Chee Hwa promised to
build at least 85,000 public and private flats annually, to
achieve a home ownership of 70 percent in 10 years, and to reduce
the average waiting time for public rental housing to three years.
</P>
<P>
To hit the targets, the government has mapped out a five-year
land sales program to enlarge supply of land.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971208.0048 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> South Korean Unemployed to Exceed 1 Million Next Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, December 8 (Xinhua) -- South Korea's top labor official
said Monday that the number of the country's unemployed is likely
to reach 1.25 million next year.
</P>
<P>
The expanded jobless population, said Labor Minister Lee Ki-ho,
is partly due to a 3 percent economic growth called for by the
International Monetary Fund (IMF).
</P>
<P>
"The jobless rate will likely increase to 4 percent next year,"
Lee Ki-ho said in his report to an economic ministers' meeting
presided over by President Kim Yong-sam.
</P>
<P>
Based on the figure, 900,000 will lose their jobs and 350,000
more will enter the "hidden unemployment" category, as they intend
to work but give up looking for jobs in the tough economy.
</P>
<P>
"Fear of unemployment is expected to spread through society
next year," the official predicted, adding that the labor ministry
will do its best to deal with the instability.
</P>
<P>
Lee raised concerns that if the country has a lower economic
growth rate than expected, the number of the unemployed could
increase to more than 1.25 million.
</P>
<P>
To help solve the problem, he said, the government needs to
invest more in labor-intensive projects such as housing and road
construction, to create more jobs.
</P>
<P>
In a bid to handle imminent job instability, the minister said
his ministry will provide various financial aids to the unemployed
for vocational training. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
