<DOCNO> XIE19971208.0051 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Economists on Current Economic Situation in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 8 (Xinhua) -- This year, China's economy has
been in a status of "high growth and low inflation", while the
relationship among major economic indices have been the most
appropriate in recent years.
</P>
<P>
However, the long-time contradictions caused by structural
problems still exist, such as the growing difficulties faced
by some enterprises and the increasing number of laid-off workers.
</P>
<P>
These are the views expressed in an article, written by
economists from the State Council Development Research Center, on
the current economic situation in China and the economic work for
next year.
</P>
<P>
The article says the period of inflation caused by the shortage
of goods has on the whole come to an end, but the current
activities of consumers have been distorted due to structural and
policy factors.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the problems of unemployment and lack of social
security are increasing, the risks in the financial sector are on
the rise, and the country's economic growth depends more on
foreign investment and export, the article says.
</P>
<P>
The article urges people to understand the current
situation from a new angle and opposes the so-called moderate
inflation policy advocated by some economists.
</P>
<P>
On the large number of loss-making state enterprises,
the article regards it a cost the State has to pay in the process
of restructuring the state sector. However, it stresses, great
attention must be paid to the problem of unemployment.
</P>
<P>
The principle thinking for the country's economic work in 1998
should be: deepening the reform, speeding up the readjustment,
advancing amid stability, and improving the quality.
</P>
<P>
It calls on accelerating the restructuring of state firms,
stepping up reforms of the social security system, improving the
structure of consumption, bolstering industrialization of the
agricultural sector, opening wider to the outside and boosting the
export sector. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
