<HEADLINE> Ramos Nominates Ruling Party's Presidential Bet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, December 8 (Xinhua) -- President Fidel Ramos announced
tonight the ruling Lakas-NUCD party's presidential candidate for
the 1998 national polls, ending a months-long fierce race for his
blessing among the party.
</P>
<P>
Jose de Venecia, speaker of the House of Representatives, was
chosen by Ramos as the man who will carry the ruling party's
banner in the May 11, 1998 presidential elections.
</P>
<P>
Ramos made the announcement after a meeting with all contenders
for the party's presidential nomination and vice presidential
nomination.
</P>
<P>
Ramos was given the blanket authority to endorse the party's
presidential candidate during the party's consultative caucus on
November 19.
</P>
<P>
De Venecia's candidacy will be formally confirmed at the
party's national convention scheduled to be held in January.
</P>
<P>
Ramos' decision was unexpected to many political observers and
the opposition camp which has been ready to celebrate the break-up
of the ruling party due to the row for Ramos' anointment as his
successor.
</P>
<P>
Ramos had been expected by the opposition to give his
endorsement to former defense secretary Renato de Villa, a retired
general who has a similar background with Ramos.
</P>
<P>
If Ramos chose de Villa, de Venecia, the governing party's
secretary-general, would probably opt to break away from the
Lakas-NUCD, which he formed with Ramos in the 1992 presidential
elections. De Villa joined the ruling party just four months ago.
</P>
<P>
In explaining the bases for his endorsement of de Venecia,
Ramos said he had tabulated and analyzed carefully the results of
the survey conducted among the party during the past several
weeks.
</P>
<P>
After announcing his choice, Ramos called on the seven other
contenders to "support Speaker de Venecia, stay with the party,
and stay with me," according to a statement from the Presidential
Press Office.
</P>
<P>
Other six contenders for the candidacy included Finance
Secretary Roberto de Ocampo, Socio-economic Secretary Cielito
Habito and Senator Ramon Magsaysay.
</P>
<P>
"All of them (other contenders) pledged enthusiastically to
close ranks and rally behind the choice of the president to ensure
the victory of Lakas in next year's polls," said the statement.
</P>
<P>
While the defeated contenders were asked to give their options
for an elective position, Ramos said that the party's vice
presidential candidate should also be known after five or six
days.
</P>
<P>
Ramos also announced that the complete senatorial slate of the
party will be known after about 15 days or before Christmas. The
country's congressional and local polls will be held
simultaneously with the presidential elections.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
