<HEADLINE> EU Trade Balance With U.S. Back in Credit: Eurostat </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, December 8 (Xinhua) -- The European Union's trade
balance in goods with the United States registered a surplus of
1.6 billion ECUs (2 billion U.S. dollars) in 1996, Eurostat said
today.
</P>
<P>
Figures, released today by the EU's statistical office based in
Luxembourg, showed that the EU's same trade balance with the
U.S. was 1.4 billion ECUs (1.7 billion dollars) in the red in 1995.
</P>
<P>
Its exports grew 11.8 percent to 114.2 billion ECUs (137
billion dollars) while imports increased 8.7 percent to 112.7
billion ECUs (135 billion dollars) in 1996.
</P>
<P>
The most important "players" in the EU-U.S. trade were Germany,
Britain, France and the Netherlands, who account for two-thirds of
the total.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, the U.S. accounted for 19.5 percent of total extra-EU
imports of goods and 18.3 percent of exports. Nearly 38 percent of
total EU outflows of foreign direct investment (FDI) went to the
U.S. which provides 70 percent of EU FDI inflows. 
</P>
</TEXT>
