<HEADLINE> Pakistan Minister Foresees Economy Turnaround in 1998 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, December 8 (Xinhua) -- Pakistani Finance Minister
Sartaj Aziz today predicted a "turnaround" in the country's
depressive economy in the first quarter of 1998.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press conference here, he said the country's
economy is expected to recover due to decline in trade deficit and
inflation as well as better performance in agriculture and
manufacture.
</P>
<P>
The trade deficit has registered a decline by 33 percent in the
first five months of the current fiscal year beginning from this
July, and fell to 618 million U.S. dollars from 2,117 million
dollars of the same period last year, he said.
</P>
<P>
Foreign exchange reserves rose from 722 million dollars in
November 1996 to 1,400 million dollars at the same month of this
year, the minister pointed out.
</P>
<P>
The inflation rate was brought down to 8.5 percent from 11-13
percent in the past four years, he said.
</P>
<P>
The agriculture sector is expected to achieve the growth target
of 5 percent despite damage to the cotton crop, the minister said.
</P>
<P>
</P>
