<BODY>
<HEADLINE> WHO: 600,000 Die of Typhoid Every Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, December 8 (Xinhua) -- The World Health Organization
(WHO) announced today that at least 600,000 people die of typhoid
every year, 70 to 80 percent of them are in Asian countries.
</P>
<P>
WHO bacteriologist Bernard Ivanoff said at the opening of the
13th Typhoid Symposium in Bali, Indonesia, that typhoid also
infects 16 to 33 million people a year and most of them live in
developing countries, according to reports reaching here this
evening.
</P>
<P>
"The typhoid bacteria grows in a place where the sanitation and
hygiene systems do not function well," he said, adding that this
bacteria usually attacks the respiratory system.
</P>
<P>
Up to now, "antibiotic therapy is sufficient to treat typhoid
for now," he said, adding that but there is no vaccine to prevent
this disease.
</P>
<P>
The three-day symposium is attended by 200 participants from
the United States, Canada, the United Kingdom, Mexico, Japan,
Singapore, Malaysia, Egypt, India, Australia and Indonesia.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
