<DOCNO> XIE19971208.0069 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Top Spiker Declines Invitation from Italian Club </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 8 (Xinhua) -- China's star spiker Zhang Xiang
declined an invitation from an Italian first division club,
preferring to play in the Chinese volleyball league, a Chinese
sports official said here on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Zhang, the best attacker of Asia, was afraid that he could meet
tough pressure and challenge in a country that has the world's
most successful volleyball league, said Gao Shenyang, gerneral
secretary of the Chinese Volleyball Association (CVA).
</P>
<P>
"Of course he will not be as good as in China if he plays in
Italy," Gao said. But he failed to reveal the name of the Italian
team.
</P>
<P>
This was the second time for the national to receive an
invitation from an Italian club. Last year, Zhang was invited to
play in the Italian volleyball league for a season with being
offered house, car and tens of thousands U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
But the CVA, who was worried that his departure could harm the
inaugural Chinese volleyball league, refused the invitation on his
behalf.
</P>
<P>
However Wang Jiawei, who took over the national squad early
this year by halting his ten-year coaching career in Japan, threw
all his weight behind the national spikers to play abroad,
especially in Europe and the United States.
</P>
<P>
"It's the best way to have a deep understanding of world's most
advanced techniques and improve the players' quality," said Wang,
who led China to regain the Asian champion in October.
</P>
<P>
China's volleyball, which once was Asia's domain in early 1980s
and a strong force in the world, lags far behind the rising tide
of professionalism, which has fully embraced soccer and basketball.
</P>
<P>
No Chinese spikers have signed clubs in Europe or America and
the Chinese volleyball league remains an all-Chinese affairs.
</P>
<P>
"There is still a long way to go before introducing foreign
players to our home league though we are making efforts to this
end," Gao said.
</P>
<P>
The second season of Chinese volleyball league starts on late
December, with eight men and eight women squads clashing on a home
and away format. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
