<DOCNO> XIE19971208.0070 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> No Change of Housing Program in Hong Kong: Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, December 8 (Xinhua) -- A senior Hong Kong official
today reiterated that the Special Administrative Region (SAR)
government has no plan to change its housing program, which is
aimed to build 85,000 flats a year starting from 1999.
</P>
<P>
Bowen Leung, Secretary for Planning, Environment and Lands,
told a group of surveyors today: "Let me say, once again and
categorically, that the government is determined to implement the
housing program. It is a long-term objective, and there is no plan
whatsoever to change it."
</P>
<P>
SAR Chief Executive Tung Chee Hwa outlined in his first policy
address in October the housing program and related land sales
plans, with the aim of sustaining annual production of at least
85,000 flats in the next decade.
</P>
<P>
Leung said today at the Hong Kong Institute of Surveyors'
luncheon that the housing land would be made available on the
basis of the first Five-Year Land Disposal Program (LDP),
announced in July this year.
</P>
<P>
Under the LDP, the SAR government will provide 120 hectares of
land for private housing up to March 1999, and an additional 260
hectares in the following three years. Over the same period, about
285 hectares of land will be used for public sector housing.
</P>
<P>
Sky-high housing prices have posed a tough challenge for the
SAR government, who has targeted to enlarge land and housing
supply so that up to 70 percent of the Hong Kong people can own
their own houses in ten years' time.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
