<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria to Amend Money Laundering Decree </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, December 8 (Xinhua) -- The Nigerian government is set to
amend its money laundering decree promulgated two years ago to spell
out more severe penalties for bank officials who aid or abet money
laundering.
</P>
<P>
A top official of the money laundering surveillance unit of the
Central Bank of Nigeria was quoted by today's Business Times as saying
that the new law will crack down on banks failing to take appropriate
action to stem money laundering activities.
</P>
<P>
According to the official, some bank are complying with the
provisions of the degree by reporting suspicious transactions to the
central bank, but others are defaulting in this area.
</P>
<P>
The official, however, did not give details on the nature of the
amendament.
</P>
<P>
Under the existing decree, transfer to or from a foreign country of
funds or securities of a sum greater than 10,000 U.S.Dollars or its
equivalent shall be reported to the central bank.
</P>
<P>
The report shall cover the nature and amount of the transfer as
well as the names and addresses of the sender and receiver.
</P>
<P>
Banks are also required to seek information from their customers as
to the origin and destination of the funds, the aim of the transaction
and the identity of the beneficiary, where a transaction whether or
not it relates to money laundering, is surrounded by conditions of
unusual or unjustified complexity.
</P>
<P>
Financial institutions are also required to report to the National
Drug Law Enforcement Agency within seven days any single lodgement,
transaction or transfer of funds in excess of 500,000 or two million
Naira (about 6,250 or 25,000 dollars) or the equivalents in case of an
individual or corporate body.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, some banks may have shunned the decree,
arguing that to carry out its directives would scare away their high
networth customers.
</P>
<P>
Others said that the provisions run counter to the traditional
confidentiality suppose to exist in banker-customer relationships.
</P>
<P>
Though the drug control agency has prosecuted some car dealers
under the decree, the central bank has so far not charged any bank
officials with flouting the decree, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The government promulgated the money laundering decree in 1995 in a
effort to combat the activities of narcotics dealers deemed as the
major source of illicit money.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971208.0074 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-08 13:34 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tehran in Tight Security for Islamic Summit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, December 8 (Xinhua) -- Tight security has been
enforced in Iran's capital city of Tehran on the eve of the
eighth Islamic summit as heads of state are arriving.
</P>
<P>
Unusual measures have been taken to the surprise of foreign
guests. Most of the highways and main streets leading to the
venue of the summit and residences of the Islamic leaders were
closed to the public.
</P>
<P>
Four-day holiday for government offices, schools and
universities and other state institutions was announced as of
today for the three-day summit of the Organization of Islamic
Conferences (OIC) due to open Tuesday with the participation of
more than 30 monarches, sheikhs, presidents and prime ministers
from 55 Islamic states.
</P>
<P>
The city with a population of over 10 million has thus been
deserted and it has turned deadly quiet. But cross roads,
streets and even alleys on the southern slope of the Alborz
mountain have stationed with groups of police with AK-47
rifles.
</P>
<P>
Police cars with red alarm lights on were patrolling up and
down the highways and streets decorated with colorful flowers and
green grass, while flags of the 55 Islamic states were fluttering
in the wind.
</P>
<P>
Dozens of heads of state, including Palestinian National
Authority President Yasser Arafat, Kuwait Emir Jaber al-Sabah,
Qatari Emir Sheikh Hamad Bin Khalifa al-Thani and Saudi Crown
Prince Abdullah Ibn Abdul-Aziz, have arrived at the Tehran
Mehrabad international airport but refrained from talking to 100
odds reporters who had been waiting there since the small hours of
the day.
</P>
<P>
Security personnel lined up in a distance of a hundred meters
each along the streets from the Tehran Mehrabad international
airport on the western outskirts to northern part of the city
where the foreign dignities are to stay.
</P>
<P>
Thorny issues have been discussed and draft resolutions of
more than 140 endorsed by OIC foreign ministers in their
just-concluded two-day sessions here, paving the way for the
eighth OIC summit.
</P>
<P>
The Tehran Declaration to be adopted by the summit will cover
all problems facing the Islamic world. Iran is trying its utmost
with patience and reconciliation to make the summit a success,
another thrust towards breaking U.S. isolation against it.
</P>
<P>
The 27-year-old Islamic body has recommended that the summit
be entitled "session of dignity, dialogue and participation,"
bringing friends and foes alike together in confrontation with
the U.S. and Israel in particular. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
