<HEADLINE> Shanghai Develops Financial Services to Support Real Estate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, December 8 (Xinhua) -- "The time is right for booming
financial services to support the development of Shanghai's real
estate industry," according to Di Weiping, deputy director of the
Shanghai Branch of the People's Bank of China.
</P>
<P>
Di made the remarks today at a Shanghai financial seminar on
real estate and finance. He said that Shanghai will witness the
rapid growth of financial and banking services related to the real
estate industry due to the city's recent economic achievements and
the country's successful housing reform.
</P>
<P>
The seminar was jointly sponsored by the Shanghai Branch of the
People's Bank of China, the Shanghai Branch of China Construction
Bank and U.S-based Morgen Stanley Asia Limited.
</P>
<P>
"Many ramshackle houses in Shanghai are in critical need of
repair and affluent residents hope to move in comfortable houses
to improve their living environment," according to Di.
</P>
<P>
However, financial and banking services catering to the
development of Shanghai's real estate industry remain somewhat
immature, and the city needs more related services, said Di.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai initiated housing reform in the early 1990s, and is
currently approaching its goal of providing commodity housing for
sale to Shanghai residents.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that the city's total outstanding loans for
housing have grown to 17.8 billion yuan over the past few years,
with individual mortgage loans rising by 120 percent in the first
half of this year.
</P>
<P>
Zhang Enzhao, director of the Shanghai Branch of the China
Construction Bank pointed out that the city needs to readjust the
structure of housing loans and credits, and establish an insurance
system for individual mortgage loans. Shanghai also needs to adopt
regulations concerning the sector and perfect the administration
system for housing loans and financial services, according to
Zhang.
</P>
<P>
Seventy Chinese and foreign experts attending the seminar
exchanged views concerning the possibility to increase both
housing deposits and the purchasing capacity of local residents in
order to revitalize Shanghai's real estate market. 
</P>
</TEXT>
