<HEADLINE> Beijing Residents Gain Internet Access </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 8 (Xinhua) -- The number of Internet users in
Beijing, the Chinese capital, has grown dramatically to more than
100,000 over the past three years.
</P>
<P>
"Beijing residents are equally enthusiastic about gaining
access to the Internet as they were installing residential
telephones years ago," according to an article in today's Beijing
Daily.
</P>
<P>
The actual number of Internet users is most likely somewhat
larger since several people often share one Internet account.
</P>
<P>
This year alone, CHINANET, which is managed by the Beijing
Telegraph Bureau, has enrolled 2,300 new users. CHINANET
offers preferential services such as reduced rate to renowned
scientists, including over 400 academicians with the Chinese
Academy of Sciences and the Chinese Academy of Engineering.
</P>
<P>
Universities, research institutes, banking and financial
institutions and trade corporations account a large majority of
the users, with a constant increase in the number of individuals
joining the network.
</P>
<P>
Individuals account for over half of the CHINANET users and an
ever increasing number of business people are learning to use the
Internet to promote their business, according to the article.
</P>
</TEXT>
