<HEADLINE> Rafsanjani Hopes for Broader Tehran-Cairo Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, December 8 (Xinhua) -- Chairman of Iran's State
Expediencies Council and former Iranian President Hashemi
Rafsanjani today expressed hope for broader relations
between Iran and Egypt.
</P>
<P>
The Islamic Republic of Iran believes that there are common
views between Tehran and Cairo, Rafsanjani said in a meeting
with Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr Moussa, according to the
Iranian official news agency IRNA.
</P>
<P>
Egypt is a powerful and effective state in the Muslim world
and can make constructive efforts to coordinate the Islamic
world, he said.
</P>
<P>
Rafsanjani stressed that the Islamic states should take
practical steps to deal with the interventionist policy of the
Israeli government and solve the regional problems.
</P>
<P>
He hoped that the three-day summit of the Organization of
Islamic Conference (OIC) to be opened here Tuesday could be a
turning point in fostering unity and solidarity among the
Muslims and tackling the difficulties created for the Muslims.
</P>
<P>
Moussa, currently in Iran for the OIC summit, said that the
regional and international developments have brought about a
closer relations between Iran and Egypt.
</P>
<P>
He said the Middle East peace process has been deadlocked,
accusing the Israeli government of its "inhuman and anti-peace
approach" which has caused annoyance of the Arab states.
</P>
<P>
The Muslim world has faced with numerous difficulties and
Egypt has pinned strong hopes on the OIC summit to find ways out
of the current situation, he added.
</P>
<P>
Relations between Iran and Egypt was severed in 1979 after
the later signed the David Camp Accord with Israel.
</P>
<P>
Both Tehran and Cairo have expressed their readiness for a
full resumption of ties. 
