<HEADLINE> ADB Gives Infrastructure Loans to Indonesia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, December 8 (Xinhua) -- The Asian Development Bank (ADB)
has approved loans worth more than 250 million U.S. dollars to
Indonesia for the development of infrastructure in its eastern and
western provinces.
</P>
<P>
The Manila-based bank said today that a 116 million dollars
loan will be given to improve basic infrastructure services in
Medan, the capital of Indonesia's North Sumatra province.
</P>
<P>
Under the Metropolitan Medan Urban Development Project funded
by the loan, over 3 million residents will benefit from better
water supply, sanitation, flood control, drainage facilities and
roads in the provincial capital.
</P>
<P>
The project will improve, widen and extend over 80 kilometers
of roads and bridges, extend flood control works on major rivers
and improve over 300 kilometers of drains.
</P>
<P>
The ADB said the project will promote the economic development
in the Indonesia-Malaysia-Thailand growth triangle, where North
Sumatra province is located.
</P>
<P>
The loan, which will come from the bank's ordinary capital
resources, is repayable over 25 years, including a 5-year grace
period.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia will receive another ADB loan of 124 million dollars
to build a new airport in Eastern Kalimantan province and upgrade
two other airports in the provinces of West Kalimantan and West
Irian Jaya.
</P>
<P>
The ADB will also provide a technical assistance grant of
975,000 dollars to the Indonesian aviation authorities to
facilitate the private sector's participation in the airport
development project.
</P>
<P>
The ADB today also announced a 800,000 dollars concessional
loan to help restore economic activity and key social and physical
infrastructure in the cyclone-battered northern part of the Cook
Islands.
</P>
<P>
The interest-free loan will be from the bank's Special Funds
resources and will be repayable over 40 years, including a grace
period of 10 years.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971208.0079 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia's Stock Shares Close Sharply Higher </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, December 8 (Xinhua) -- Shares on the Kuala Lumpur
Stock Exchange closed sharply higher today following austerity
measures announced by the Malaysian government.
</P>
<P>
At the close, the Composite Index was up 11.37 percent or 69.07
points to 676.47, the Emas Index rose 15.81 points to 175.28 and
the Industrial Index gained 57.41 points to 1,249.80 while the
second board index rose 4.54 points to 239.76.
</P>
<P>
Gainers overwhelmed losers 716 to 54 while 52 counters were
unchanged and 77 untraded.
</P>
<P>
On the main board, turnover today increased to 432.462 million
shares valued at 1.716 billion ringgit (470.1369 million U.S.
dollars) compared to 220.726 million valued at 695.168 million
ringgit (190.4569 million U.S. dollars) last Friday when the
market started surging following the government's announcement of
austerity measures.
</P>
<P>
On the second board, turnover rose to 33.186 million shares
valued at 95.205 million ringgit (26.0835 million U.S. dollars)
compared to 21.977 million shares valued at 77.704 million ringgit
(21.2887 million U.S. dollars) last Friday.
</P>
<P>
Off-market deals increased to 47.914 million shares valued at
132.281 million ringgit (36.2416 million U.S. dollars) compared to
18.524 million valued at 75.833 million ringgit (20.7761 million
U.S. dollars) last Friday.
</P>
<P>
The rally today and last Friday were due to positive reactions
to the government's austerity measures announced on Friday and
additional austerity measures announced today, according to
analysts.
</P>
<P>
They said the market was encouraging by the measures including
a 18 percent cut in the government expenditure and a 10 percent
pay cut for the ministers and deputy ministers.
</P>
<P>
They said there would be some profit taking and tighter
liquidity before the end of the week, but the CI is not expected
to dip below the 600 level.  
</P>
</TEXT>
