<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australian Armed Forces to Be Cut by 12 Percent in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, December 8 (Xinhua) -- The Australian Defense Force
(ADF) is set to cut almost 7,000 more uniformed personnel from its
ranks over the next three years, taking uniformed numbers to about
50,000, or 12 percent of the total.
</P>
<P>
ADF spokesman Colonel Andrew Reynolds confirmed today that the
Royal Australian Air Force was set to lose 3,000 personnel, the
army 2,500 and the navy 1,000, the Australian Associated Press
reported.
</P>
<P>
The government's Defense Reform Program, adopted earlier this
year, pointed to substantial savings through rationalization of
defense activities.
</P>
<P>
It said staff reductions of some 3,100 civilians and 4,700
uniformed personnel were anticipated. The defense organization is
now well on its way to shedding staff, with total recurrent
savings put at almost 1 billion Australian dollars (about 700
million US dollars).
</P>
<P>
The savings would be used by the armed forces to fund part of
its modernization program.
</P>
<P>
"The chief of the Defense Force has said a couple of times
publicly that we are going to bring the Defense Force down to
about 50,000," Reynolds said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
