<HEADLINE> Disarmament Representatives to Visit All Bases in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FREETOWN, December 8 (Xinhua) -- Representatives of the west
African peacekeeping force ECOMOG and the military junta of
Sierra Leone have agreed to visit all bases in the capital and
the interior of all combatants involved in the country's crisis.
</P>
<P>
The decision was reached by ECOMOG and Sierra Leonean military
government representatives to the Technical Committee on
Disarmament at a recent meeting in Freetown, Bashiru Conteh, Head
of the disarmament committee said today.
</P>
<P>
Head of the disarmament committee, Bashiru Conteh of the
Sierra Leone said, "We have agreed that the visits should begin
on December 10 and end on December 22 in order to assess the task
ahead."
</P>
<P>
"We are on course as we've agreed to include other civil
defense groups in our discussions regarding the peace process,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
According to Conteh, the delegates have already discussed the
selection and assessment of all disarmament sites, set up
guidelines of operations, codes of disarmament, the provision of
data as well as the classification of all arms and ammunition
received from combatants.
</P>
<P>
Asked which group will be disarmed, Conteh replied, "This is
not for me to decide. This will be looked into and decided by
higher authorities."
</P>
<P>
"My duty is to see that modalities for the disarmament process
are worked out effectively," he added.
</P>
<P>
Sources close to the talks said the Kamajors, the leading
warring defense unit sent an eight-man delegation to the meeting,
the first time the group has met face to face with government
representatives. 
</P>
</TEXT>
