<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ECOWAS Stops Lending Due to Arrears of Members' </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, December 8 (Xinhua) -- The Economic Community of West
African States (ECOWAS) has stopped all forms of lending due to
more than 27 million U.S. Dollars of debt being owed by its
member states in unpaid capital contribution and loans.
</P>
<P>
ECOWAS finances its development projects through the ECOWAS
Fund, but the huge deficit has put the fund into a "precarious
financial situation" as described by ECOWAS Chairman, Nigeria's
Head of State General Sani Abacha.
</P>
<P>
According to Abacha, the fund has been running deficit budget
for the past two years and it will be operating a deficit budget
in 1998, preventing the institution from effectively performing
its financial functions.
</P>
<P>
In a message to the 30th session of the Board of Directors of
the fund last Friday in Abuja, the Nigerian capital, Abacha said
further loaning from the fund's resources has been frozen as a
result of the financial situation.
</P>
<P>
The ECOWAS chairman suggested that urgent steps be taken to
complete the on-going restructuring of the fund in order to
enable it to attract the much needed resources from non-regional
investors.
</P>
<P>
The Secretariat of ECOWAS earlier lamented the failure of
member states to pay their membership fee, making it unable to
execute many community programs of the 16-member sub-regional
body.
</P>
<P>
As of last June, member states owed ECOWAS about 44.7 million
U.S. Dollars. The debt included arrears of between three to 17
years as well as contributions for this year.
</P>
<P>
To solve the problem, ECOWAS leaders decided at their August
summit to impose a community levy to replace contribution by
member states for funding community projects beginning next year.
</P>
<P>
The 0.05 percent levy will be imposed on all imports into the
sub-region from third countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
