<HEADLINE> Australian Dollar Drops On Depressed Gold Prices </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, December 8 (Xinhua) -- The Australian dollar fell to
a new four-year low today, driven down to 66.85 U.S. cents by
depressed gold prices and anxiety over the domestic impact of the
Asian currency crisis.
</P>
<P>
The Australian dollar closed at 67.11 U.S. cents, from 67.25
U.S. cents late Friday, after reaching a high of only 67.16 U.S.
cents.
</P>
<P>
Traders said the local currency was continuing to trend lower
on concerns about the Asian crisis and the gold price in lieu of
domestic fundamentals.
</P>
<P>
Sydney trading in gold bullion closed at 287.70 U.S. dollars an
ounce from 286.85 at Friday's close.
</P>
<P>
SBC Warburg Australia foreign exchange director John Radinoff
said the currency fell to 66.85 U.S. cents today, marking another
new four-year low for the Australian dollar.
</P>
<P>
It was last at these levels in December 1993.
</P>
<P>
Radinoff said trading was extremely quiet today due to lack of
interest in buying the Australian dollar.
</P>
<P>
"There still seems to be export interest down at 67 U.S. cents
and below, and there didn't seem a lot of reason to buy it," he
said.
</P>
<P>
Also disappointing the market today was news that the Federal
Government had not opted as expected to remove the 10 percent
interest withholding tax on interest payable to non-residents
holding Commonwealth and state government bonds.
</P>
<P>
The government instead decided to widen tax exemption to
include corporate debentures only.
</P>
<P>
Against the yen this evening, the Australian dollar was at
87.05 from 87.34 Friday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
