<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Africa's NP Calls for Death Penalty Summit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, December 8 (Xinhua) -- South Africa's
oppositlion National Party (NP) has urged the government
to hold a referendum and summit on the reintroduction of the death
penalty
</P>
<P>
NP safety and security spokesman, Piet Matthee, said in a
statement Sunday that the summit should be convened to investigate the
possible reintroduction of capital punishment within three
months, according to media reports.
</P>
<P>
The summit should investigate the moral and legal implications
and be convened by a multi-party committee to hear arguments for
and against the death penalty's reintroduction, Matthee said.
</P>
<P>
The ruling African National Congress has been vehemently
opposed to the restoration of the death penalty on the grounds
that the capital punishment is barred by the constitution.
</P>
<P>
South Africa abolished the death penalty on the eve of the
first democratic elections in 1994.
</P>
<P>
The NP made the call after the conviction of a serial killer
Moses Sithole last week, at which Justice David Curlewis said it
as a "mistake" to have done away with the death penalty.
</P>
<P>
Sithole was sentenced to 2,410 years in prison after being
found guilty of 38 counts of murder, 40 rapes and six cases of
robbery.
</P>
<P>
The Zulu-based Inkatha Freedom Party last month introduced a
bill to amend the constitution so as to allow for the death
penalty, but it is believed that the bill will be vetoed at the
committee level and would not be able to reach the ANC-dominated
National Assembly.
</P>
<P>
ANC President Nelson Mandela, who had been in prison for 27
years, personally abominated the death penalty on the grounds
that it was used as a major tool by the apartheid regime to
oppress the black majority.
</P>
<P>
The issue, which Mandela said should never be reopened, became
hot again when Western Cape Premier Hernus Kriel, a member of the
NP, called for a referendum in his province last month.
</P>
<P>
The question of death penalty looks set to be a matter for
debate in the 1999 general election as there is louder and louder
calls from the society for the restoration along with spiraling
crimes. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
