<HEADLINE> Philippine Senate to Verify Marcos' Bank Accounts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, December 8 (Xinhua) -- Ferdinand Marcos, Jr., son of
Philippine late president Ferdinand Marcos, today authorized a
Senate committee to look into the bank accounts allegedly
controlled by his father.
</P>
<P>
The young Marcos submitted to the Senate Blue Ribbon committee
a letter officially requesting concerned banks to reveal the
transactions which the Marcos family had entered into.
</P>
<P>
The committee disclosed the existence of 93 bank accounts of
the Marcoses which are not covered by the 500 million U.S. dollars
being pursued by the government.
</P>
<P>
The Philippine government has filed litigation cases against
the Marcoses to recover the alleged ill-gotten wealth amassed by
the family of the former president.
</P>
<P>
The young Marcos insisted that no such accounts exist, and was
confident that investigation into the so-called Marcos wealth,
particularly the Marcos gold hoard, will end up nowhere.
</P>
<P>
But still, he proposed that the government directly request the
countries where the bank accounts were opened to assist in
uncovering the alleged wealth. 
