<HEADLINE> Indonesia Spends Huge Sum for Dengue Patients </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, December 8 (Xinhua) -- The Indonesian government spent
up to 47 billion rupiah (13.4 million U.S. dollars) every year to
finance the medical treatment of about 45,000 dengue patients, a
health ministry official said today.
</P>
<P>
"Although we have been trying to combat the dengue cases since
1995, meaningful progress have not been achieved so far including
reducing the number of the cases and the contaminated regions,"
Director General for Contagious Disease Prevention Dr. Hadi M.
Abednego said at a symposium on dengue.
</P>
<P>
Dengue fever, an acute tropical disease, leaves its victims
with fever, rash and severe pains in the joints and back. The
cholera-like disease spread by mosquitoes, known locally as
"muntaber", also causes vomiting and diarrhea.
</P>
<P>
Dr. Abednego said the number of people infected with dengue
increased from 35,000 in 1995 to 45,000 in 1996 in Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
And by November this year, some 22,500 people had been infected
with the disease, he added.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the death rate among dengue patients also rose from
2.5 percent in 1995 to 2.7 percent in 1996. By November this year,
2.1 percent of the total dengue patients had died, he said.
</P>
<P>
The disease occurs in 162 districts, 778 sub-districts and
2,402 villages across the country, he said.
</P>
<P>
According to the World Health Organization, the number does not
really reflect the actual situation as many have missed a diagnose
and died.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
