<HEADLINE> Australian Stocks Close Up On Back Of Wall Street </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, December 8 (Xinhua) -- Shares in Australia finished
at their highest level today since late October on back of Wall
Street, but slightly off their intraday highs, as investors sought
profits in late afternoon trading, brokers said.
</P>
<P>
"It was very strong over the day on the back of Wall Street,"
said Peter Struk of Reynolds &AMP; Co, adding that brokerage firms had
sold in late afternoon trading for profit-taking and the premium
over the futures market.
</P>
<P>
The all ordinaries closed up 29.8 points at 2587.0, after
reaching a high of 2597.2 and a low of 2557.2. The close was the
highest since late October. On Friday, the Dow Jones Industrial
Average closed up 98.97 points at 8149.12.
</P>
<P>
National turnover was 313.25 million shares and valued at
949.68 million Australian dollars (636.28 million U.S. dollars).
Rises outnumbered falls 641 to 421, with 364 stocks remaining
steady.
</P>
<P>
The all industrials index was up 43.9 points at 4418.7 and the
all resources index was up 19.3 points at 1127.8.
</P>
<P>
A high trader was Accor Asia Pacific Company Ltd. with a
turnover of 7.016 million shares.
</P>
<P>
Telstra Corp. installment receipts, which have not yet been
weighted into the all ordinaries index, gained seven cents.
</P>
<P>
Among the major recourses companies, BHP gained 27, MAC gained
12 and Rio Tinto gained 60 cents.
</P>
<P>
D&AMP;D Tolhurst today reported that the worst of the Asian
currency crisis was already over for resource stocks and buying
should now recommence. Other analysts and brokers were more
cautious on the impact of Asia on commodities.
</P>
<P>
National Australia Bank was up 30 cents, Westpac Banking Corp
was up nine, Commonwealth Bank of Australia was up 15 and ANZ
Banking Group was up 19.5. 
</P>
</TEXT>
