<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> TDC to Focus on Promotion of HK's Competitiveness </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, December 8 (Xinhua) -- The Hong Kong Trade
Development Council (TDC) today announced a refocusing of its
promotional efforts next year on Hong Kong's competitiveness.
</P>
<P>
Speaking of TDC's global promotional program for 1998,
Executive Director Michael Sze said: "We are redeploying resources
 to competitiveness, the key issue facing Hong Kong, and indeed
the entire Asia-Pacific, as we prepare for the next century."
</P>
<P>
For the past several years, the council has allocated much
energy in easing concerns in overseas markets about Hong Kong's
post-handover prospects. "Now that the transition is successfully
behind us, confidence in Hong Kong's future is no longer a big
issue for our trading partners," he said.
</P>
<P>
Sze said important groundwork for the shift in focus has been
done over the past two years, when the council has taken a lead in
 major research studies on Hong Kong's economy and the sources of
its competitiveness.
</P>
<P>
"But there is no doubt that the issue has been given extra edge
 by the Asian currency crisis and a round of competitive
devaluation in the region," he noted.
</P>
<P>
The TDC will act on two levels: first, highlighting Hong Kong's
 competitive strengths across the world; second, directly helping
the thousands of small and medium-sized enterprises (SMEs) which
form the backbone of Hong Kong's economy and its competitiveness.
</P>
<P>
TDC's strategy emphasizes practical help for the 300,000 SMEs
in Hong Kong, upgraded market information particularly from the
inland areas of China, and a mix of initiatives to more vigorously
 promote Hong Kong's value-added economy, Sze said.
</P>
<P>
In addressing the financial crisis in the region, Sze said Hong
 Kong will be positioned as a partner offering unique financial
and professional services to neighboring countries.
</P>
<P>
The council will also be stepping up its efforts on the
mainland by instituting a series of fact-finding missions to find
out how Hong Kong-based companies can take advantage of business
opportunities as Chinese state-owned enterprises (SOEs) are
restructured.
</P>
<P>
Plans include creating a detailed databank on SOEs and
developing dialogs between Hong Kong business people and senior
SOE executives.
</P>
<P>
"One of the cornerstones of Hong Kong's competitiveness is our
role as China's international business hub and our increasingly
important function of providing funding and expertise for the
mainland's modernization," said Sze.
</P>
<P>
As a direct help to SMEs, a dedicated SME information center
and a well-equipped training facility for practical workshops will
 be set up in the expanded Convention and Exhibition Center.
</P>
<P>
TDC is also looking to further promote Hong Kong's services, a
key area of competitive advantage for the local economy. A series
of anchor exhibitions have been planned for major sectors such as
finance, information technology, design and marketing.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971208.0101 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Flower Industry Blossoms in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 8 (Xinhua) -- China's flower industry is
booming as an increasing number of affluent Chinese are learning
how to brighten their life with flowers.
</P>
<P>
Statistics released during the Third Executive Council of the
China Flower Association (CFA), which opened today in Beijing,
show that the nation's area under flower plants in 1996 reached
75,000 hectares and the industry recorded a total output
value of 4.8 billion yuan (578 million US dollars), up 60 percent
on 1993.
</P>
<P>
The export value for flowers jumped from 50 million US dollars
in 1993 to 130 million US dollars last year, the statistics show.
</P>
<P>
Chen Muhua, vice-chairman of the Standing Committee of the
National People's Congress and honorary president of CFA, told
participants of the meeting that China enjoys favourable climatic
and geological conditions, and has abundant human resources to
develop the flower industry.
</P>
<P>
According to CFA sources, southwest China's Yunnan Province has
developed into China's major fresh flower production base, with
south China's Guangdong province as the country's production
center for decorative plants.
</P>
<P>
Chen said that China should use the experiences of
countries such as the Netherlands and Japan which have highly
developed flower industries.
</P>
<P>
The CFA, founded in 1984, has joined a number of international
flower organizations, including the International Horticultural
Producers Association and the World Rose Federation.
</P>
<P>
CFA President He Kang said the association held China's first
flower trade fair in Shanghai, the nation's largest city, in April
this year. He noted the event attracted some 100 enterprises from
14 countries and regions, and ended with a total business volume
of some 20 million yuan.
</P>
<P>
He added that the CFA will sponsor an international flower
exposition in Shanghai in 1998, and an international horticulture
fair in Yunnan Province in 1999.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971208.0102 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia Announces 10 Percent Pay Cut for Ministers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, December 8 (Xinhua) -- Malaysian Deputy Prime
Minister Anwar Ibrahim today announced a 10 per cent pay cut for
ministers and deputy ministers as one of the "Strategic Measures
to Strengthen the Country's Economic and Financial Stability."
</P>
<P>
The salaries of officers in Super scale C and above, political
secretaries and those holding equivalent posts would be cut by
three per cent, Anwar, who is also Finance Minister, announced in
Parliament.
</P>
<P>
Anwar said the decision was made after the holders of these
posts offered to have their salaries cut.
</P>
<P>
He said the government had also decided to freeze salary
increment for government officers in the A and B categories until
the economy recovers.
</P>
<P>
The finance minister said that in line with this move, the
government hopes that the private sector will take similar
measures to ease the inflationary pressure on the country.
</P>
<P>
He said that to extend the incentives for the tourism sector
and make domestic tourism more attractive, a 10 per cent tax break
on service tax and five per cent on sales tax on rooms would be
given to all hotels in the country.
</P>
<P>
To prevent outflow of funds and to encourage domestic tourism,
ministers and civil servants who enjoy travel and vacation
benefits are no longer allowed to tour overseas, he said.
</P>
<P>
Anwar said that in line with this, companies giving their staff
travel and vacation benefits to travel within the country would
continue to receive tax reduction. However, the same benefits, if
used for overseas travel, would no longer be given tax reduction.
</P>
<P>
The deputy prime minister said for the education sector, the
entry of experienced foreign tutors would be simplified in efforts
to ensure a high standard of education in the country while in
keeping with the current economic situation, the government had
taken the step to reduce in stages the number of students sent
overseas starting next year.
</P>
<P>
On the property sector, Anwar said the industry must make urban
renewal an important component of its strategic thinking in the
long run and in this respect, housing developers and the banking
system would be encouraged to widen the concept of redeveloping
old housing estates, whether government-owned or
private-sector-owned.
</P>
<P>
"Property developers will continue to be given incentives and
facilities to build more low-and-medium-cost houses," he said.
</P>
<P>
On December 5, Anwar already announced several measures towards
economic recovery and restoring investors' confidence including a
18 per cent cut back in federal government spending.
</P>
<P>
He scaled down the country's growth to between four and five
per cent of Gross Domestic Product (GDP) from the earlier forecast
7 percent next year.
</P>
<P>
He announced reducing the current accounts deficit in 1998 from
four to three per cent of GDP; deferring all major projects;
ensuring banks' safety as the guiding principle in deciding
between the interests of the banks and their debtors; protecting
depositors in the banking system; freezing applications for new
listings, rights issues and corporate restructuring; and
reaffirming the government's commitment to a flexible exchange
rate regime.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971208.0103 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 56 Thai Finance Firms Ordered to Close Down </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, December 8 (Xinhua) -- Thai Finance Minister Tarrin
Nimmanhaeminda announced today that 56 of the 58 earlier-suspended
finance companies had been ordered to close down, leaving only two
allowed to reopen.
</P>
<P>
Operations of the 58 finance firms were suspended in June and
August this year by the Chavalit Yongchaiyudh Administration
because of their massive debts and lack of liquidity. Their bad
debts severely bogged down a number of commercial banks.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press conference today, Tarrin said the mass
closure was a major step in restructuring the country's financial
sector and will lead to increased investor confidence, inflow of
foreign capital and stability of the weakening Thai baht, which
has lost more than 60 percent of its value against the U.S. dollar
since its floating in July .
</P>
<P>
The bad assets of the closed-down finance firms will be handled
by a newly-established asset management corporation, which may
sell the bad assets at auction.
</P>
<P>
About 6,000 employees of the shut-up firms will be made
redundant in accordance with Thailand's labor law.
</P>
<P>
The Stock Exchange of Thailand (SET) reacted positively to the
mass closure, with its index rising 3.35 percent from the last
trading day, reversing the falling trend of last week.  
</P>
</TEXT>
