<HEADLINE> Common Maritime Policy Envisaged for 24 African </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, December 8 (Xinhua) -- A unified maritime policy may
soon be adopted by 24 west and central African countries to boost
the development of the industry in the two sub-regions.
</P>
<P>
The step is intended to enable the countries responsible to
changes in international maritime transport, especially in the
Area of Trade Liberalization, the weekly Business Times reported
today.
</P>
<P>
It will not only match developments in international maritime,
but also ensure that the sub-regions maximize the benefits of the
sector to their economy's advantages.
</P>
<P>
Transport ministers of the 24 countries are scheduled to meet
in Abuja, Nigeria, between December 9 and 12 to ratify
recommendations on the maritime policy and other issues made at
the previous session of the Ministerial Conference of West and
Central Africa on Maritime Transport (MINCOMAR).
</P>
<P>
MINCOMAR, which is coordinating the policy formulation, has
already directed at its 9th ordinary session general assembly
that member states should adopt new strategies to make the
proposed policy a reality.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, the ministers will ratify
deliberations on the reform of shippers council, definition of a
new strategy for the redeployment of shipping lines and maritime
ancillary activities and the establishment and implemention of
short- and medium-term sub-regional integration projects in
international shipping.  
</P>
</TEXT>
