<HEADLINE> Zambia Concerned over Dumping of Banned Chemicals </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, December 8 (Xinhua) -- A senior Zambian official today
expressed the government's deep concern over continued dumping of
banned chemicals on the third world countries by industrialized
nations, Zambia News Agency (ZANA) reported.
</P>
<P>
Officially opening a three-day workshop held in Lusaka on
sound management of chemicals for countries in Southern African
Development Community (SADC), Peter Mwamfuli, Permanent Secretary
of the Ministry of Environment and Natural Resources, said that
the victims of such exports have been innocent people in the
third world countries.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that the use of such chemicals which are
creating serious environmental and human health hazards has led
to thousands of deaths in the third world countries as the level
of awareness among the users is not very good.
</P>
<P>
The Zambian official called for a regional approach towards
the prevention of banned chemicals into the developing countries.
</P>
<P>
Mwamfuli urged countries that are exposed to chemical
disposals to work together to address the problem.
</P>
<P>
For over ten years, he said, Zambia has 300 metric tons
of obsolete pesticides lying around in the open and creating
serious health problems. 
</P>
</TEXT>
