<HEADLINE> CIS Executive Secretary Confident in Its Future </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, December 8 (Xinhua) -- The Commonwealth of Independent
States (CIS) has not been exhausted, and there are no alternatives
to it, CIS Executive Secretary Ivan Korotchenya said today in
Minsk, Belarus.
</P>
<P>
Korotchenya was quoted by the Interfax news agency as saying
that six years are too short to say that the CIS has failed. He
believes that the CIS has done its job.
</P>
<P>
It has "created a real basis for comprehensive cooperation of
the states and formed an essentially new political, organizational
and legal framework for voluntary cooperation," Korotchenya said.
</P>
<P>
He believed that the CIS is recognized throughout the world as
a large regional organization.
</P>
<P>
The executive secretary said that in certain cases, the member
states may have to cede their interests for the sake of
coordinating joint activities, otherwise the economic and other
integration might be "problematic".
</P>
<P>
Korotchenya added that the union of Belarus and Russia is not
an alternative to the CIS, which was founded on December 8, 1991,
after the former Soviet Union collapsed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
