<HEADLINE> Manila Declares Busting of Three Kidnap Syndicates </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, December 8 (Xinhua) -- The Philippines' Presidential
Anti-Crime Commission announced today the busting of three
kidnap-for-ransom gangs in a concerted action against kidnappers.
</P>
<P>
During the action, 25 kidnap suspects including four of their
leaders, who victimized mostly wealthy Chinese-Filipino
businessmen, were arrested, it said.
</P>
<P>
The fall of the suspects gave heat to the anti-kidnapping drive
launched at the beginning of the month by the anti-crime
commission and its various affiliated units from the National
Bureau of Investigation and the national police.
</P>
<P>
According to Justice Secretary Teofisto Guingona, the fall of
the kidnappers brought solutions to nine cases in which the
suspects blackmailed for some 1 million U.S. dollars in ransoms.
</P>
<P>
Guingona said that five of the 25 suspects were involved in the
kidnapping and murder of Gordon Tan, son of a wealthy shop owner,
on November 24.
</P>
<P>
The killing of Tan and another young Filipino Chinese
businessmen by abductors promoted the Filipino-Chinese community
to stage a series of protests and urge President Fidel Ramos to
stop kidnappings.
</P>
<P>
Ramos told the chiefs of the law enforcement departments that
he "wanted to see results" of the campaign against kidnappers.
</P>
