<HEADLINE> Japan Freezes GSP Treatment on 44 Thai Exports </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, December 8 (Xinhua) -- The Japanese government has
suspended Generalized System of Preference (GSP) treatment on 44
Thai exports, according to the Nation today.
</P>
<P>
At present, Thailand is enjoying preferential trade treatment
under the third 10-year GSP program from April 1991 to March 2001.
The GSP concessions were granted to 125 groups of products,
covering both industrial and agricultural goods.
</P>
<P>
Japanese officials claimed that the number of Thai goods taking
advantage of the GSP has by far exceeded the ceiling set by Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
However, the Thai Commerce Ministry expects Japan will continue
to be a key market for Thailand, as Thai exports have become more
competitive after the Thai baht has depreciated by more than 60
percent against the U.S. dollar since July 2 float.  
</P>
</TEXT>
