<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Launches Two U.S.-made Iridium Satellites </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 8 (Xinhua) -- A China-made rocket
successfully carried two U.S.-made satellites into orbit at
3:16:49 P.M. today (Beijing time) from the Taiyuan Satellite
Launch Center in north China's Shanxi Province.
</P>
<P>
Chinese carrier has thus fulfilled all launching tasks set for
the year, scoring successes for six launches in a row.
</P>
<P>
This was also the 49th launch of the Long March rocket family,
according to corporate sources.
</P>
<P>
Initial results from Xi'an Satellite Monitoring and Control
Center indicated that the satellites, made by Motorola Corp. of
the United States, and the rocket separated 50 minutes after
launch.
</P>
<P>
The two satellites were positioned at the low-earth orbit with
a perigee of 629 km, an apogee of 632 km and a bank angle of 86.3
degrees, marking the successful end of the commercial launch
undertaken by China Great Wall Industry Corp.
</P>
<P>
Motorola has contracted the Great Wall group to launch another
10 iridium satellites in coming years.
</P>
<P>
The launch used an improved version of China-developed Long
March 2C, with an initial propelling capacity of 213 tons.
</P>
<P>
According to officials with Motorola, the iridium satellite
system is a global wireless communications network that will
combine its worldwide reach of 66 low-Earth-orbit satellites with
land-based wireless systems. Subscribers to the network will have
a variety of telecommunications services -- such as telephones and
paging services -- virtually anywhere in the world.
</P>
<P>
Today's launch also marked the debut of Taiyuan Satellite
Launch Center in the international commercial launching
market. Three decades of efforts have turned the center into an
all-round player capable of launching various satellites into
orbit. Two China-made FY-1 meteorological satellites have been
launched from this center.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971208.0121 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Round-up: New Opportunity for Private Economy (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 8 (Xinhua) -- As state enterprises are
accelerating the transfer of property rights under new reform
schemes, the non-state sector in China is facing another
historical opportunity for expansion.
</P>
<P>
In a major move, the inland Shaanxi Province in the
less-developed northwestern China has decided to grant private
businesses equal rights with state-owned enterprises in obtaining
bank loans and acquiring land, as well as water and power supply
and transportion.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai, China's leading industrial and commercial center,
recently came out with a series of policies encouraging
Sino-overseas joint ventures, private and collectively-owned
firms, and share-holding companies to launch new and high-tech
enterprises, as well as encouraging technicians to take stakes or
setting up high-tech companies of their own.
</P>
<P>
In its new policies, Shijiazhuang, capital of north China's
Hebei Province, stresses providing support to large-scale private
enterprises, including issuing a "protection card" to these
enterprises to reduce their burdens and enjoy a good production
environment.
</P>
<P>
Beijing has decided that qualified non-state enterprises will
be given approval to issue stocks and bonds, and will enjoy
reduced taxes. Guangzhou, capital of south China's Guangdong
Province, has also followed suit.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971208.0122 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Round-up: New Opportunity for Private Economy (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Chinese economists have also been airing their support for
expansion of the private sector.
</P>
<P>
Xiao Zhuoji, a renowned economist at Peking University,
stressed the need to improve the competitive environment so the
non-state sector can enjoy equal terms with the state sector.
</P>
<P>
Economist Wang Zhuo advocates establishing a modern enterprise
system that would ensure the introduction of non-state property
rights mechanism through the market.
</P>
<P>
Private businesses that emerged in the early 1980s have already
become part of the national economy through decades of
development. However, the sector still plays a supporting role in
China's political and economic life.
</P>
<P>
The 15th National Congress of the Communist Party of China held
in September issued a call for further expansion of the private
economy. Analysts believe this has provided a new opportunity for
further development of the non-state sector.
</P>
<P>
The private sector can take advantage of the reorganization of
assets and the transfer of property rights of state enterprises,
experts say, adding that the private sector should shift the focus
of its business from the countryside to the cities, and from
commerce, trade and processing to industry and high-tech field.
</P>
<P>
Many private enterprises are now actively involved in acquiring
state enterprises. For example, most of the 50 million yuan (6.024
million U.S. dollars) of the share capital of the Shanglian
(commercial alliance) Group in Harbin, capital of northeast
China's Heilongjiang Province is held by private enterprises.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
