<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shanghai Boosting Tourism </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, December 8 (Xinhua) -- Shanghai has decided to expand
tourism industry and plans to turn the sector into a new economic
powerhouse for the city.
</P>
<P>
According to a goal set recently for developing the tourism
industry, by 2000 Shanghai expects to annually attract two million
overseas tourists and 100 million domestic visitors, and earn 20
billion U.S. dollars. The added value from tourism would account
for 6 percent of the municipality's gross domestic product (GDP).
</P>
<P>
Yao Mingbao, executive deputy director of Shanghai's Municipal
Tourism Commission, explained that the city would have to increase
the number of foreign tourists by 10 percent and domestic visitors
by 15 percent in the next three years to meet the goals.
</P>
<P>
He said that goal can be reached as long as arduous efforts are
made and sound measures are practiced to explore tourism industry.
</P>
<P>
Yao said his commission will take measures to boost tourism
such as establishing six service organizations and tourism
enterprise groups, developing chain management companies, pooling
funds from society to form share-holding companies for developing
tourism, advancing development and production of tourist
commodities, tightening management of the tourist market and
strengthening training of professional tourism personnel.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai's tourism sector has been operating more than 40
tourist routes and more than 400 scenic sites, and has added new
tourist programs of special features while intensifying its
promotional work in overseas tourist markets. In 1996, overseas
tourists stayed in the city for an average of 4.3 days, an
increase of 16 percent over the previous year.
</P>
<P>
The municipality has also decided to practice a strategy of
seeking simultaneous development of overseas and domestic tourism
by adjusting its existing tourism strategy which involved focusing
only on international tourism.
</P>
<P>
The Shanghai Municipal Tourism Commission has cooperated with
concerned local departments to build an all-embracing service
network for tourism development.
</P>
<P>
The city has also dispatched missions to other parts of the
country to publicize Shanghai's tourism resources, hoping to build
a multi-level tourist network with concerned departments of other
areas on the basis of mutual benefits.
</P>
<P>
In the first ten months of this year, the city received 1.38
million overseas tourists, a rise of 16 percent over the same
period last year. More than 50 million domestic tourists visited
Shanghai during the same period.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971208.0125 </DOCNO>
