<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Singapore's Manufacturing Output Up by 6.4 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, December 8 (Xinhua) -- Singapore's manufacturing
output increased by 6.4 percent in October, compared to the same
month of last year, as most of the major industries continued to
record higher output except for the pharmaceuticals and plastic
industries, the Economic Development Board (EDB) said today.
</P>
<P>
As a result of the increase in October, the cumulative output
growth for the first ten months of this year was 3.1 percent over
the same period of last year, it said.
</P>
<P>
In October, the output of electronic products was 4.2 percent
higher compared to the same month last year, with higher
production of semiconductors, computer peripherals and printed
circuit board assembles.
</P>
<P>
However, the EDB said, there was lower output of personal
computers and telecommunication equipment due to fewer orders from
the United States and China respectively.
</P>
<P>
For the first ten months of 1997, cumulative output of the
electronics industry grew by 1.6 percent compared to the same
period of last year.
</P>
<P>
The chemicals industries, including petroleum, petrochemicals,
pharmaceuticals and industrial/specialty chemicals, maintained a
steady growth in October. The year-on-year increase was 17.5
percent in October 1997 and 17.1 percent for the first ten months
of the year.
</P>
<P>
The machinery and equipment industry increased by 17.7 percent
due mainly to more work done in the fabrication of oil rigs and
higher output of lifting machinery, conveyors and metal working
machines. Cumulatively, output for the first ten months of the
year grew by 5.9 percent.
</P>
<P>
The output of rubber and plastic products fell by two percent
in October with lower output of components for consumer
electronics. But the output of plastic packaging materials, tubes
and pipes increased.
</P>
<P>
Cumulatively, the output for the January-October period was 7.2
percent less than the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
The output of pharmaceuticals declined for the second month in
October, down by 25.9 percent, the EDB noted. It said that the
decline was caused by a temporary shutdown of a plant for
cleaning. The cumulative output for the first ten months was
marginally higher by 0.4 percent from the corresponding period
last year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971208.0127 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-08 10:36 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: Islamic Leaders Seek to Close </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, December 8 (Xinhua) -- Iran has been quick to declare
victory in hosting the Islamic summit, which it says symbolizes
that it did not fall victim to the isolation and containment
attempt plotted by the United States.
</P>
<P>
"We do not feel isolated," said a ranking Iranian official
while fielding questions at a press conference on whether the
summit will act on Washington's long-standing hostile policies
against Tehran.
</P>
<P>
This feeling is perhaps shared by some other time-tested foes
of the U.S. - Libya, Iraq, Sudan, to name a few - whose leaders or
high-ranking officials are scheduled here Monday for the eighth
summit of the Organization of the Islamic Conference (OIC) on
December 9-11.
</P>
<P>
More than 30 monarches, sheiks, presidents and prime ministers
are said to turn up at the summit, represented by all the 55 OIC
member states but Afghanistan, whose seat was preferred to be
kept vacant due to the nebulous situation of civil conflict in
the country. Afghan President Burhanuddin Rabbani will be present
at the summit as an observer.
</P>
<P>
The 27-year-old Islamic body has agreed to define the
upcoming get-together as a "session of dignity, dialogue and
cooperation," an expectation it has tried hard to conceive.
</P>
<P>
With one fifth of the world population and rich resources,
the Islamic countries have been eager to iron out their grudges
and differences, and close ranks; they are even more so now in
the face of the latest developments in the international arena
and at the threshold of a new century.
</P>
<P>
This was reflected in the just-concluded Islamic foreign
ministers' meeting in preparation for the summit. The past two
days witnessed a barrage of draft resolutions in the fields of
politics, economy and culture gaining endorsement of those
ministers.
</P>
<P>
They were differing on many issues, of course. But they
reconciled, trying to seek common ground while shelving
differences. For example, the summit is expected to oppose
Islamic countries' military cooperation with Israel, in general
and in principle, but refrain from calling names. It will also
condemn the "expansionist policies" and "hegemonism" of Israel
and the United States.
</P>
<P>
This reasonable approach has evidently cleared the way for
the summit to become time-efficient in working out a strategy
for the organization's future role and objectives.
</P>
<P>
As OIC Secretary General Izziddine Al-Iraki put it, there are
many developments in store in the next century, the Islamic
world "should be prepared to take calculated stances on those
developments while maintaining its values and principles."
</P>
<P>
Not only will the Islamic leaders discuss such political
topics as Arab-Israeli conflict, Jerusalem, Bosnia-Herzegovina,
U.S.-Libyan crisis over the Lockerbie aircraft bombing,
Afghanistan, Kashmir and many others, but also they will focus
attention on unity and solidarity, as well as "all-out
cooperation" among Muslim countries.
</P>
<P>
There is going to be roaring diplomacy, on bilateral or
multi-lateral bases, on the sidelines of the summit. Iran and
Egypt which cut off diplomatic ties 17 years ago, for example,
have said they believe this summit is helpful to improve
their relations.
</P>
<P>
Ankara and Tehran are said to be ready to send their recalled
ambassadors back to work next month, while Turkish President
Suleyman Demirel is to be in town today.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the summit will also put emphasis on
intra-Islamic economic, scientific and technological cooperation,
among other things.
</P>
<P>
The idea of establishing an Islamic common market is set to
attract much interest. The leaders have yet to draw a
step-by-step plan to enable such an ambitious common market to
take shape.
</P>
<P>
More conspicuous is the summit being held in the immediate
wake of a botched U.S. attempt to bring together Arab Muslim
leaders and Israelis in the November conference on economic
cooperation in Doha, Qatar. The meeting met outright boycott by
a majority of Arab countries, which cited lack of progress in
the Middle East peace process as the reason.
</P>
<P>
Actually they blamed the U.S. policy as "not impartial," but
in favor of Israel at the sacrifice of Arabs and Palestinians,
and condemned the Israeli government as "hard-line" and
expansionist."
</P>
<P>
The Islamic leaders now gather in Tehran, much to the
resentment of the U.S. and Israel, to try to speak in one voice
and make it heard in the rest of the world. Should they succeed
in settling bitter divisions, this goal can be achieved.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
