<DOCNO> XIE19971208.0128 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-08 09:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel's Redeployment Map Won't Be Ready Soon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, December 8 (Xinhua) -- The Israel's final map on
next troop redeployment in the West Bank may not be ready when
Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu meets U.S. Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright again on December 17 in Brussels.
</P>
<P>
This assessment by local media was based on the latest session
of the Israeli four-member cabinet committee, which was held here
Sunday shortly after Netanyahu's return from Paris, where he
conferred twice with Albright on the redeployment issue.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu briefed the committee on his just-concluded European
trip, but the committee only decided to appoint two
subcommittees of topographical and security experts to crystalize
a map of national interests and security and then submit them to
the committee for consideration.
</P>
<P>
Although its general outlines of demarcation of territory to
be ceded to the Palestinian National Authority (PNA) and the
concepts behind it are almost certain to be in hand, it is in
doubt that it would be complete in time for Netanyahu's next
meeting with Albright in Europe when she returns from Africa.
</P>
<P>
Besides Netanyahu, the newly formed cabinet committee in
charge of making decisions on troop redeployment in the West
Bank also includes Defense Minister Yitzhak Mordechai, Foreign
Minister David Levy and National Infrastructure Minister Ariel
Sharon.
</P>
<P>
Big differences exist among the four members. Sharon prefers
to have a 20-kilometer-wide Jordan River Valley security zone in
the East and another seven to 10 kilometers wide security zone
along the 1949 Armistice Line in the West of the West Bank. But
Levy said that it may not be accepted by the PNA.
</P>
<P>
Because of Mordechai's official visit to Turkey, the committee
will not reconvence until after Mordechai's scheduled return
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
On Saturday, during her meeting with Netanyahu in Paris,
Albright urged Israel to decide on a swifter, more credible
withdrawal from the West Bank than Netanyahu has promised.
</P>
<P>
But Netanyahu said that there will be no government's final
decision on the depth of the redeployment by December 17, the
government's discussion will likely go on until the end of
December.
</P>
<P>
French Foreign Minister Hubert Vedrine said in Paris Sunday
after meeting with Netanyahu that France holds that Israel's
plans for a promised troop pullback from the West Bank are
insufficient. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
