<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Regulation Governs Accounting at State-Owned Enterprises </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 8 (Xinhua) -- China's Ministry of Finance has
issued a new regulation to improve supervision of accounting
practices in state-owned enterprises.
</P>
<P>
All enterprises should reasonably arrange their spending under
the principle of "production first and consumption second," the
regulation urges.
</P>
<P>
Project budgets and spending plans should be compiled and
approved by the congress of worker representatives and the board
of directors.
</P>
<P>
The regulation stipulates that increases in an enterprise's
total salary should be lower than the growth of its economic
returns, while the actual rise in average employee salary of an
enterprise should be lower than that of work efficiency.
</P>
<P>
Investment in fixed assets should be made only after the need
for operating funds is met, the regulation says.
</P>
<P>
Business activities between related enterprises must be managed
through separate and independent accounting, it says, adding that
a sheet reporting system should be established.
</P>
<P>
Enterprises should set up necessary internal fund distribution
schemes and strict internal cost control systems, the regulation
says.
</P>
<P>
To ensure the smooth implementation of the regulation, the
Ministry of Finance has also issued a notice calling for financial
and accounting administrations at all levels to conduct effective
supervision over accounting in enterprises. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
