<DOCNO> XIE19971208.0132 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Daewoo to Take over Ssangyong Motor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, December 8 (Xinhua) -- Daewoo Group will take over Ssangyong
Group's auto unit within this month, making it the first merger and
acquisition (M&AMP;A) case in the IMF-led reform movement.
</P>
<P>
Daewoo Motor Chairman Kim Tae-gou and Ssangyong President for
planning Kim Duk-hwan held a joint press conference Monday morning,
formally announcing that the two will be signing a contract to hand
over Ssangyong Group's 53.5 percent stake in its car-making unit to
Daewoo this month.
</P>
<P>
The takeover will go into effect on December 15.
</P>
<P>
Ssangyong, the nation's sixth biggest largest business group,
decided to sell its debt-ridden automaking subsidiary to ease the
managing crisis due to the tight financial flows.
</P>
<P>
Under the two group's agreement, Daewoo will assume over 2
trillion won (1.6 billion US dollars) of Ssangyong Motor's total
debts of 3.4 trillion won. Ssangyong will shoulder the remaining
liabilities.
</P>
<P>
The takeover of Ssangyong Motor, the first case after the
International Monetary Fund (IMF) asked South Korea to undergo
restructuring by M&AMP;As, would change the landscape of South Korea's
glutted auto industry.
</P>
<P>
Daewoo, the nation's second largest auto-maker and fourth
biggest industrial giant, will fill the business vacancy of
commercial motor vehicle by the takeover.
</P>
<P>
Daewoo started its takeover bid at a time when the domestic auto
industry is undergoing restructuring due to production glut and
shifted to Ssangyong Motor from Kia Group's Asia Motor for takeover
target, in consideration of Ssangyong vehicle's popularity.
</P>
<P>
Daewoo hopes to build a two-tier structure in the local auto
industry, to help it pit against Hyundai Motor Co., the nation's
largest automaker, industry sources said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
