<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Making Progress in Human Gene Study </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 8 (Xinhua) -- A human genome project which
involves researchers from 16 Chinese institutes has produced an
enormous amount of significant data, according to the National
Natural Science Fund Committee.
</P>
<P>
The project, "Studies on Several Gene Loci Structure of the
Chinese Human Genome," has three sub-projects, said a committee
official in charge of the project.
</P>
<P>
The sub-projects include building a bank of immortalized cell
lines to reserve genes from representative nationalities and
endangered ethnic minorities, introducing and upgrading new
techniques of human gene science and studying the position of the
gene related to human diseases, he said.
</P>
<P>
Scientists have found abundant resources for their human gene
studies in China, which has 22 percent of the world's total
population, 56 different nationalities and several separated human
groups, the official said.
</P>
<P>
Participants in the project said they have completed 733 cell
lines of two groups of Han nationality in southern and northern
China, and 12 ethnic minorities in southwest and northeast China,
and conducted comparative studies on the diversity of Chinese
multi-nationality genomes.
</P>
<P>
Researchers have also made progress in cloning a group of genes
related to such human ailments as leukemia.
</P>
<P>
The project can help form a cooperative system of human gene
studies in China, which includes many outstanding research groups.
</P>
<P>
The cooperative system, along with data banks and research
centers built for the project, will enable the country to carry
out studies on genome diversity, self-positioning, cloning of
disease-related human genes, genes linked to human functions and a
large-scale survey of DNA orders.
</P>
<P>
Experts said the results of the project and related
improvements in the country's human gene study will help China
make further developments in the field.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
