<HEADLINE> Israeli Nationwide Strike Causes Serious Economic </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, December 8 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Treasury has
estimated the cost of the five-day-old nationwide strike launched
by the Trade Union (Histadrut) against the government economic
reform plans at 300 million shekels (about 86 million
U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
The Jerusalem Post reported today that the crippling general
strike, which came to an end Sunday night after the Trade Union
and the Finance Ministry reached a compromise over pension
dispute, has dealt a serious blow to the country's economy.
</P>
<P>
Finance Minister Ya'acov Neeman was quoted as saying that the
understanding could have been reached without the strike, which he
said did damage to exports and the tourist industry.
</P>
<P>
While the Israeli Manufacturers Association said the total cost
of the strike, which had paralyzed the country by effectively
shut down airports, post offices, banks, government offices and
state-owned companies, was 195 million shekels (about 56 million
U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
"Workers in industry and those on low pay in the business
sector themselves are those most likely to be harmed", the
association's economist, Shuki Abramovitz, said.
</P>
<P>
He expected that the damage would be felt in lost wages and loss
of customers. In addition, industrialists have already started
complaining of a lack of raw materials as a result of the
strike.
</P>
<P>
Another concern is losing competition of Israeli goods abroad
after foreign buyers saw Israeli exporters missing
deadlines. Abramovitz said the Federation of Chambers of Commerce
decided to file damage claims against strike leaders.
</P>
<P>
Trade Union Chairman Amir Peretz apologized for the hardships
the strike caused to the public, but said that "a society which
wants a recognized and protected workers' class, must accept the
temporary suffering."
</P>
<P>
The nationwide strike was the latest round of the Trade
Union's battle against economic reform plans of the government,
which have sparked fears that the workers' rights will be
harmed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
