<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pilot Region Set up for Pushing Ecological Economy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HEFEI, December 8 (Xinhua) -- Chizhou, China's only pilot
prefecture for developing an ecological economy, has enhanced
efforts in environmental protection by strictly controlling
factories that pollute and by encouraging clean production methods.
</P>
<P>
The prefecture, in east China's Anhui Province, has given
priority to a number of green technology projects, mainly in
agriculture.
</P>
<P>
A 66,666-hectare garden of fruit trees is under cultivation and
ecological tourism is being encouraged by the prefecture,
according to local officials.
</P>
<P>
The prefecture, with a forestry coverage rate of 52.5 percent,
has three unpolluted, state-level nature reserves with rich
resources. Lakes and reservoirs are scattered throughout the
region known for the Jiuhua Mountain.
</P>
<P>
China is pushing the ecological economy in an attempt to
simultaneously coordinate growth and environmental protection. The
State Planning Commission has set a goal of 50 county-level pilot
regions for ecological economy before the end of the century.
</P>
<P>
The knowledge gained from the pilot regions will be shared
nationwide, officials said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
