<DOCNO> XIE19971208.0146 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Quality Problems Found Among Imported Goods </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 8 (Xinhua) -- Commodity inspection
authorities in Beijing said that inspections of imported
foreign goods has uncovered serious quality problems.
</P>
<P>
During the July-October period, the Beijing Administration for
the Inspection of Import and Export Commodities checked 598 lots
of imported goods. The inspection revealed that 142 lots, or 23.75
percent of the goods, failed to meet quality standards.
</P>
<P>
The inspection found that capital goods such as high-precision
machine tools, complete sets of equipment, aeronautical products
and medical apparatus were shopworn, damaged or had parts
missing.
</P>
<P>
An administration circular calls for special attention to the
quality of imported raw chemicals and medicine.
</P>
<P>
Local sources said the inspected goods are worth 160 million
U.S. dollars and importers intend to demand compensation for an
estimated 5.8-million-yuan items. 
</P>
</TEXT>
