<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Airport in Nanjing Opens to Foreign Aircraft </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANJING, December 8 (Xinhua) -- The State Council, China's
highest governing body, has opened Lukou Airport in Nanjing,
capital of east China's Jiangsu Province, to foreign aircraft.
</P>
<P>
Lukou is the first airport in the province accessible to
overseas planes.
</P>
<P>
Opened July 1, the airport has a runway 3,600 meters long and
60 meters wide, and a taxiway 3,600 meters long and 45 meters
wide, capable of accommodating jumbo jets such as the Boeing
747-400.
</P>
<P>
Three Chinese airlines are currently based at the airport and
22 airlines have opened routes linking 40 large- and medium-size
Chinese cities.
</P>
<P>
Between July 1 and Nov. 28, 12,245 landings and take-offs were
recorded at the airport.
</P>
<P>
Since Nov. 26, daily outbound and inbound flights increased to
more than 750 over 57 routes. 
</P>
</TEXT>
