<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gansu Acupuncture Research Institute Set up </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LANZHOU, December 8 (Xinhua) -- The Gansu Fushan Heated
Acupuncture Research Institute, the first of its kind in China,
was recently established in Lanzhou, capital of northwest China's
Gansu Province.
</P>
<P>
The institute will focus clinical treatment using heated
acupuncture needles and related research.
</P>
<P>
The use of heated acupuncture needles dates back well over
2,000 years.
</P>
<P>
This particular medical practice differs from normal methods of
heating acupuncture needles prior to inserting into acupoints.
</P>
<P>
Tian Fushan, director of the institute and an expert in the
field, studied acupuncture as a child and has developed the skill
using heated acupuncture needles to treat disorders.
</P>
<P>
Tian has treated more than 6,000 patients suffering from bone
spurs, with all patients reporting complete recovery.
</P>
<P>
He also treats patients suffering from verrucosis, hemorrhoids
and tragomaschalia, and as well as rheumatic arthritis,
hemiparlysis, and skin carcinoma.
</P>
<P>
Tian has published over 30 research papers and numerous books
on related subject matter.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
