<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-08 08:31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Intifada Can Start Any Time: Hamas Leader </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, December 8 (Xinhua) -- On the eve of the tenth
anniversary of the intifada (Arab uprising), the Islamic
Resistance Movement (Hamas) leader in Gaza Abdul Aziz Rantisi has
warned that new intifada against Israel could start at any time.
</P>
<P>
Rantisi issued the warning in an interview with Israel's only
English daily The Jerusalem Post, which was published today,
claiming the flare of confrontation still burns within the
Palestinian people and could explode at a suitable time.
</P>
<P>
He maintained that it was Hamas which encouraged the uprising
in December 1987 by calling out from the mosques for people to
protest in response to an accident involving an Israeli
semi-trailer that collided with a Palestinian vehicle and killed
four passengers and injured 10 others.
</P>
<P>
Rantisi said pent-up feelings of injustice led to the
explosion of protests. "The intifada forced the Palestinian
people to face a reality and the continual injustice wrought
upon them by Israel. Their inner fears and frustration were
translated externally in the shape of stones, declarations,
rallies and protest marches and then the people regrouped and
headed into direct confrontation," he said.
</P>
<P>
Although most mainstream Palestinian groups consider the
intifada as having ended in 1993, with the signing of the Oslo
accords, Rantisi charged that "the Israeli government continues
to treat the Palestinians in a similar fashion, kindling the
intifada flame felt by the people."
</P>
<P>
"It is only a matter of time before it explodes again," he
said.
</P>
<P>
Rantisi vowed that Hamas, which opposes the
Israeli-Palestinian peace process, would continue its struggle
against Israel as long as Israel occupies Palestinian land.
</P>
<P>
He insisted that Hamas' political and military wings are
separate entities and that any threats regarding further attacks
come from Hamas' military wing known as Izzadin Kazzam.
</P>
<P>
In fact, Hamas has gained its fame around the world through
Izzadin Kazzam's suicide bombers, who often blew up themselves in
crowded Israeli buses, bustling markets and other public
places, inflicting heavy casualties of innocent people.
</P>
<P>
In the latest two suicide bombing attacks carried out by
Izzadin Kazzam in two central Jerusalem markets in late July and
early September, 25 people were killed and 300 others wounded by
five Hamas suicide bombers. The Israeli government has been
pressuring the Palestinian National Authority to launch an
all-out war against Hamas so to advance the peace process.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971208.0152 </DOCNO>
