<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Quake-hit County Reaps Big Harvest </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
URUMQI, December 8 (Xinhua) -- Jiashi County, shaken by seven
earthquakes measuring over 6 on the Richter Scale in less than
three months, has reported a record harvest of grain and cotton.
</P>
<P>
Farmers in the most seriously stricken Yingmaili Township of
the county in northwestern China's Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous
Region, who have been busy collecting cotton, are expecting 1,500
kilograms of ginned cotton per hectare.
</P>
<P>
"Farmers' average per capita income is estimated at 1,250 yuan,
250 yuan more than last year," said Zheng Genchang, head of the
township.
</P>
<P>
However, the series of quakes brought destructive losses to
Jiashi. Local people almost immediately began new efforts to
rebuild their homes with outside help.
</P>
<P>
The county government sent officials to every village to help
with recovery work, and invited experts from the regional Academy
of Agricultural Sciences to help prevent bollworm infestation.
</P>
<P>
Authorities also exempted farmers from agricultural taxes of 7
million yuan.
</P>
<P>
The county had 141,700 tons of grain, with a per-hectare output
450 kilograms more than last year; and 27,000 tons of cotton, 31.7
percent higher than the previous record in 1995. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
