<DOCNO> XIE19971208.0155 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More Ballot Boxes Prepared for Eventual Run-off </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, December 8 (Xinhua) -- Kenya's Electoral Commission
has placed orders for additional ballot boxes for the use in the
event of a run-off in the December 29 presidential race, the
Daily Nation reported today.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted Commission Chairman Samuel Kivuitu as saying
that his commission had to order for extra boxes in case none of
the presidential candidates garners the mandatory 25 percent
votes in at least five of the country's eight provinces, thus
necessitating a run-off.
</P>
<P>
He disclosed that the number of voting centers had increased
from 2,000 in 1992 to 13,500 during the December 29 poll, making
it necessary for the number of ballot boxes to be increased.
</P>
<P>
Kenya's law stipulates that ballot papers be returned into the
specific ballot boxes after counting and kept sealed for six
months.
</P>
<P>
This makes it impossible for the commission to use the same
boxes during the presidential run-off, which must be conducted
within 21 days of the holding of the General Election.
</P>
<P>
The commission chairman pointed out that the clearing process
had started at the Jomo Kenyatta International Airport. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971208.0156 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-08 </DATE_TIME>
