<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Africa Lifts Ban of Research Into "AIDS Drug" </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, December 8 (Xinhua) -- South Africa's Medicines
Control Council (MCC) has given a new lease of life to Virodene
P058, a drug developed locally to fight HIV/AIDS, local daily
"The Star" reported today.
</P>
<P>
The MCC announced at the weekend its turnabout, which allowed
for the renewed research into Virodene.
</P>
<P>
Virodene was formulated by former Pretoria University
researcher Olga Visser, cardiothoracic surgeon Dirk du Plessis,
and a clinical assistant Callie Landauer 18 months ago.
</P>
<P>
The discovery became public knowledge in January this year
when the trio approached the government for 3.7 million Rand
(770,000 U.S. Dollars) to continue research.
</P>
<P>
The developers claimed Virodene could reverse full-blown AIDS
to HIV, but their claims were met with disbelief and suspicion by
their peers because the clinical trials were said not have been
conducted ethically.
</P>
<P>
The MCC at the time had substantial concerns about Virodene
and banned research on it for the reason that the product was
made from "an industrial solvent with un-known impurities and was
known to be toxic".
</P>
<P>
However, on Friday last week, the MCC said it was committed to
supporting the facilitating the development of new safe drugs for
the treatment of HIV/AIDS.
</P>
<P>
Ziggie Visser, spokesman for Cryo Preservations Technology
which holds the patent for Virodene, said yesterday that a plan
was already in place to continue developing the AIDS drug, and
the results should be available in about four months' time.
</P>
<P>
Health Minister Nkosazana Zuma has expressed welcome to MCC
announcement, saying she was interested in establishing whether
Virodene was effective. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
