<HEADLINE> German Firms Step up Economic Investment in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, December 8 (Xinhua) -- German businessmen's
increasing interest and confidence in China's economic growth in
recent years have resulted in new investments.
</P>
<P>
Solely German-funded enterprises are booming. An Ipsen company
in Shanghai, with an investment of 14 million U.S. dollars, is
expected to provide advanced boilers for such industries as
automobiles and machinery in China.
</P>
<P>
Sino-German cooperation in high-tech sectors is promising. SAP,
the world's largest applicable software supplier, opened the SAP &AMP;
Compaq Competence Center in Shanghai at the end of October. SAP
expects to jointly establish a computer center with Digital Corp
here.
</P>
<P>
Apart from Volkswagen and Siemens, German investment has flowed
into new areas such as vessel manufacturing, liquid gas
transportation and drinking water supplies.
</P>
<P>
Preuss-Ruhrgas spent 72 million Deutsche marks on a container
lift factory in Xiamen in east China's Fujian Province for a 70
percent share of the enterprise. 
</P>
