<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe Praised for Efforts to Combat Drought </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, December 8 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe is well prepared to
fight the drought likely to be caused by the prevailing El Nino
weather phenomenon, a Food and Agriculture Organization (FAO)
official has said.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with local newspaper "The Herald" yesterday,
FAO Cooperation
and Food Security Officer Mark Smulders said the Zimbabwean
government had enough grain in its reserves and funds to fight
the effects of a possible drought.
</P>
<P>
He said availability of information on El Nino made it
possible for Zimbabwe and other countries in the region to put in
place drought management measures.
</P>
<P>
"Early warnings on the possibility of drought have helped the
governments and other charity organizations to put in place
measures which will help cushion the effects of drought," the
official said.
</P>
<P>
He said although some people felt that availability of
information would cause panic, FAO believed that the public had
to be well informed about any possible disasters so that they
could also gear themselves for possible difficulties.
</P>
<P>
He called on organizations which dealt directly with communal
farmers to conduct massive awareness campaigns in all areas.
</P>
<P>
"Communal farmers know their area best and if they are warned
in time they may grow early maturing crops and look for means of
cushioning themselves from the effects of drought," he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
