<HEADLINE> Chinese Vice-Premier Meets Pakistani Delegation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 8 (Xinhua) -- Vice-Premier and Foreign
Minister Qian Qichen met here today with a delegation from the
Pakistan Islamabad Council of World Affairs led by its president,
Agha Shahi.
</P>
<P>
Qian said China and Pakistan share each other's views on many
major international issues. He said that he is very happy to have
the opportunity to discuss issues of common concern with his
Pakistani friends.
</P>
<P>
Qian told Shahi that China hopes for a long-standing, peaceful
international environment for its economic advancement. He also
said the view that China's rise will pose a threat to the world is
totally groundless.
</P>
<P>
Shahi, who is also former foreign minister of Pakistan, echoed
Qian's remarks, saying that China's development over the past
years left his delegation members with a deep impression. He said
the continued development of China will be very important to the
region and the world at large.
</P>
<P>
He told Qian that the visit has enabled him and his colleagues
to engage in wide-ranging discussions with some Chinese institutes
concerning the regional situation and energy development. The
delegation had also visited Shanghai and Xi'an.
</P>
<P>
The Pakistani visitors have come to China at the invitation of
the Chinese People's Institute of Foreign Affairs.
</P>
<P>
The Islamabad Council of World Affairs is an unofficial
organization for international studies in Pakistan. It consists of
retired senior government and military officials. 
</P>
</TEXT>
