<DOCNO> XIE19971208.0166 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australia Unveils 880M US Dollar Industry Policy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, December 8 (Xinhua) -- Australian Prime Minister John
Howard today unveiled a 1.26 billion Australian dollar (880
million U.S. dollar) industry package designed to increase exports
and investment in Australian industry.
</P>
<P>
"The package of new measures announced in this statement, which
include spending of 1.26 billion Australian dollars over five
years, will further boost innovation, investment, export trade and
innovation in new, high growth industries," Howard told the
National Press Club.
</P>
<P>
The four-year package includes an additional 389 million U.S.
dollars to be directed to a major expansion of the Research and
Development Start program over the four years to the financial
year of 2001-2002.
</P>
<P>
The existing duty drawback and tariff export concession schemes
are to be consolidated into one integrated and simplified scheme
to be known as TRADEX.
</P>
<P>
The package, known as the Investing for Growth package, also
announced a manufacturing in bond (MiB) strategy to complement
TRADEX, through which imports would receive a tax break if they
were to be used to make goods which would then be exported.
</P>
<P>
"MiB will allow companies to use Australia as a base for hub
operations servicing the Asia-Pacific region without incurring
duty liability on goods intended for re-export or used as inputs
to exports," the industry statement said.
</P>
<P>
"The combined effect of TRADEX and MiB will deliver the same
outcomes as foreign trade zones and enhance Australia's
attractiveness as an investment destination," it said.
</P>
<P>
Howard said the package outlined the important initiatives
required to further enhance innovation, investment and exports and
to develop Australia's finance and information technology sectors
as vital building blocks in a coherent economic strategy.
</P>
<P>
The industry policy is part of the measures made by the
Australian government to promote economic growth and reduce high
unemployment (about 9 percent on average annually in the past five
years), one of the major social issues facing the country.
</P>
<P>
Howard said, "The overriding aim of our extensive economic
reform agenda is to deliver Australia an annual growth rate of
over 4 percent on average during the decade to 2010."
</P>
<P>
He explained strong and sustainable economic growth was the key
to significantly reducing unemployment and raising living
standards for all Australians. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
