<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenyan Police Ready to Guard Presidential </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, December 8 (Xinhua) -- The Kenyan police protection
group has been set up to provide security for 14 opposition
presidential candidates during their campaigning for the December
29 General Election, The East African reported today.
</P>
<P>
The weekly newspaper said that 75 officers of the group had
completed their training at the General Service Unit (GSU) camp
at Ruiru near Nairobi and some had already been attached to their
charges.
</P>
<P>
The decision to offer security to opposition leaders was made
at the talks by the Inter-Parties Parliamentary Group (IPPG)
about providing a level playing field for the coming general
elections.
</P>
<P>
In recent years, leaders from opposition parties have been
regularly teargassed, their meeting disrupted and their
supporters dispersed by Kenyan security forces.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted Police Commissioner Duncan Wachira as saying
last month that several of the presidential candidates had asked
for and received police protection.
</P>
<P>
President Daniel arap Moi, by virtue of his incumbency, enjoys
round-the-clock protection by an elite GSU and police
intelligence unit.
</P>
<P>
Mwai Kibaki, presidential candidate for the Democratic Party
of Kenya, and Raila Odinga, presidential candidate for the
National Development Party, are said to have their own security
details.
</P>
<P>
Last month, Commissioner Wachira pledged to make available a
security detail for each of the presidential aspirants.
</P>
<P>
The offer was seen as a goodwill gesture by the Kenyan
government following a series of constitutional reforms brought
about by the IPPG before the dissolution of the Seventh
Parliament in October. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
