<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Donates Relief Medicines to Afghanistan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, December 8 (Xinhua) -- China has donated medicines,
blankets, sweaters and other desperately needed relief items worth
about 360,000 U.S. dollars to Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
At a formal ceremony held here this morning, Chinese Economic
Councilor Fu Guangting, on behalf of the Chinese government,
handed over the substantial donation for Afghanistan to the office
of the United Nations High Commissioner for Refugees (UNHCR).
</P>
<P>
"As a close neighbor of Afghanistan's, it is our duty to give a
helping hand to the Afghan people," Fu said. "We hope that peace
will soon return to the country and every Afghan could enjoy a
normal life."
</P>
<P>
"This donation couldn't have come at a better time," said UNHCR
Chief of Mission for Afghanistan Sri Wijeratne at the ceremony.
</P>
<P>
"These items will help many Afghans, including refugees who
have returned from Pakistan and Iran, to get through what promises
to be an extremely difficult winter," Wijeratne said.
</P>
<P>
"We are really grateful to the Chinese government for this
donation," he said. "But our gratitude will be nothing compared to
that of the Afghans who will receive these items."
</P>
<P>
The shipment of medicines, blankets, sweaters, shoes and black
tea, worth a total of three million yuan (about 360,000 U.S.
dollars) reached Peshawar, a major city in northwestern Pakistan,
last week on a convoy of seven trucks after traveling down the
Karakoram Highway from China's northwestern Xinjiang region.
</P>
<P>
UNHCR officials said most of the donated relief items will be
flown from Peshawar to Bamyan province in central Afghanistan,
which is in the grip of a major food crisis and a shortage of just
everything.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
