<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More Laid-off Workers Find New Jobs (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 8 (Xinhua) -- Statistics by the State
Statistical Bureau show that four million laid-off workers
throughout China were able to find new jobs between January and
September, according to a front-page story in today's People's
Daily.
</P>
<P>
Under the planned economy, China for decades pursued a policy
of "full employment but low pay." However, inefficiency,
excessive expenditures and overstaffed factories hindered
the competitive edge of Chinese companies, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
The Central Committee of the Communist Party of China and the
State Council specified that most large- and medium-sized
companies should step out of their financial predicament and
should establish modern enterprise system within three years, it
said.
</P>
<P>
The country's coal industry, with 3.6 million workers, lost
nearly six billion yuan, or 723 million U.S. dollars, in 1991.
</P>
<P>
Between 1993 and 1996, key state-run coal mines laid off
760,000 employees, with 320,000 of those finding jobs in other
businesses.
</P>
<P>
In four years the loss was reduced by 2.49 billion yuan, 1.29
billion yuan, 940 million and 2.1 billion yuan
successively. Average productivity in the coal industry has
increased to 2.1 tons per worker from 1.33 tons per worker in
1992, according to statistics.
</P>
<P>
The re-employment project is the only way to help companies in
financial difficulties, the paper said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
