<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More Laid-off Workers Find New Jobs (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Laid-off workers should be given help to find other jobs, officials
said, because the country's insurance system is not mature enough
to deal with the large numbers.
</P>
<P>
While maintaining social stability, the country should make
full use of the talents of laid-off workers. The re-employment of
laid-off workers is important for the well-being of hundreds of
thousands of Chinese families, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai has provided job opportunities for more than 800,000
laid-off workers. The municipal government has reportedly
considered the benefits for those laid-offs.
</P>
<P>
The country's government organizations should also provide
financial support and practical policies in tandem with carrying
on the re-employment project, the story said.
</P>
<P>
Laid-off workers should also be encouraged to establish
individual or partnership businesses featuring voluntary
cooperation, self-funding and self-management.
</P>
<P>
Leaders from various levels must concentrate on improving the
quality of workers in the next century, it added.
</P>
<P>
Also, Chinese people, especially the young, must bring some
change to the current idea of job-hunting. In the past, many
Chinese regarded jobs in state-run businesses and government
offices as lifetime employment.
</P>
<P>
Another key issue, the story said, is continuous vocational
training for workers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
