<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Implements New Decision on African Elephant </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, December 8 (Xinhua) -- African elephants and elephant
products can now be exported to Europe under strictly monitored
regulations following the adoption of revised lists of wildlife
species protected from international trade by the European Union.
</P>
<P>
"The Herald" daily reported today that the revised lists
reflect in full agreements made by the parties to the Convention
on International Trade in Endangered Species (CITIES) of wild
fauna and flora at a conference in Harare in June this year.
</P>
<P>
The key changes are the opening of strictly limited and
conditional import possibilities for African elephants and
elephant products, including ivory, as well as the submission of
sturgeons and sturgeon caviar to export and import licensing.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted member of the European Commission responsible
for the environment Ritt Bjerraard as saying, "This action
demonstrates our full commitment to CITIES and our respect for
the decisions of its conference of parties."
</P>
<P>
Under the new regulations, elephant trophies for
non-commercial use from Botswana, Namibia and Zimbabwe can now be
imported into the European Union.
</P>
<P>
Leather goods and ivory carvings for non-commercial purposes
from Zimbabwe can now also be exported to the EU.
</P>
<P>
Live elephants can be exported to "appropriate and acceptable"
destinations. These would also be for non-commercial use.
</P>
<P>
All other imports into the EU of African elephants and their
products remain strictly prohibited.
</P>
<P>
The subsequent sale of ivory products imported from Zimbabwe
is prohibited as all ivory carvings are to be for non-commercial
personal use.
</P>
<P>
The EU said the changes opened the way for possible
experimental resumption of trade in existing stocks of ivory
between Botswana, Namibia and Zimbabwe and Japan.
</P>
<P>
However, the EU said this would not start before March 18,
1999, adding that a series of strict conditions would have to be
met first.
</P>
<P>
The EU said the international trade in wildlife was not only a
significant industry worldwide but could also contribute to
biodiversity loss and threaten some species with extinction.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
