<DOCNO> XIE19971208.0184 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippines Told to Hold On to Tight Fiscal Policies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, December 8 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government has
been told by the World Bank that it should maintain tight fiscal
and monetary policies if it wants to ensure financial stability
and keep investor's confidence in the economy.
</P>
<P>
The World Bank acknowledged that the monetary policies
implemented after the de facto devaluation of the peso had been
"appropriate" but said "the tradeoffs involved have inevitably
caused policy tensions to rise," local newspaper the Business
Daily reported today.
</P>
<P>
"Tight monetary policies are called for to adjust to the
diminished demand for domestic assets, to limit the extent of
exchange rate depreciation and increase in inflation, and to
maintain the confidence of international creditors, exporters and
overseas workers," the World Bank said in its macroeconomic
report.
</P>
<P>
But meanwhile, the bank said the Philippines' adjustment to the
financial storm had been "relatively rapid and certainly better"
than that of its neighbors. It added that this was evident despite
policy tensions that arose from conflicting policies triggered by
the shift in market sentiment.
</P>
<P>
The bank viewed the country's performance as different from
that of other nations in Southeast Asia, noting that the period of
significant foreign borrowing by the private sector and rapid
credit growth was shorter in the country when compared with its
neighbors.
</P>
<P>
"As a result, the ratio of private credit to gross national
product is more modest, large corporations appear less leveraged
and vacancy rates for vulnerable segments of the real estate
market appear lower," the World Bank said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
