<DOCNO> XIE19971208.0185 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Guangzhou Raises Funds to Build More Urban Projects </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, December 8 (Xinhua) -- Guangzhou, capital of south
China's Guangdong Province, has succeeded in increasing its urban
building fund by 400 percent in the past five years.
</P>
<P>
Guangzhou's city government used to be the sole investor in the
city's infrastructure construction before 1980, with an investment
of less than 10 million yuan a year.
</P>
<P>
Because of this low level of funding, the city was not able to
keep up with the rapid economic development due to China's reform
and opening-up.
</P>
<P>
The city government then took advantage of non-governmental
sources to greatly improve fund raising for capital construction,
pushing up the figure from 1.37 billion yuan (about 171 million
U.S. dollars) in 1992 to 6.74 billion yuan (about 842 million
U.S. dollars) in 1996.
</P>
<P>
According to a city official, non-government funds mainly come
from securities, overseas funding, and loans from foreign
governments and organizations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
