<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Six Thousand Beijing College Graduates to Choose Their Own Jobs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 8 (Xinhua) -- In China the state used to pay
tuition for college students and assign them to jobs after
graduation, but that is changing.
</P>
<P>
Next year 6,126 college graduates in Beijing, under China's new
policies, can choose their own jobs. These graduates account for
12 percent of the class of '98, according to the Beijing Municipal
Education Committee.
</P>
<P>
The 6,126 students are at 13 colleges and universities,
including such top schools as Beijing and Qinghua universities.
</P>
<P>
The state adopted a "pay-to-learn" scheme in 1994 where
students were responsible for their own tuition, said Gan Beilin,
director of the student job assignment division.
</P>
<P>
The state still provides some employment services to graduates
such as holding talent exchange markets and offering employment
information.
</P>
<P>
According to official sources, more and more students have
taken to choosing their own jobs. About half of Beijing's
graduates in 1999 will have to choose their own jobs, and by 2001
all graduates in China will have to that. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
