<BODY>
<HEADLINE> WB Lauds Tanzanian Economic Performance </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, December 8 (Xinhua) -- The World Bank expressed
satisfaction over Tanzania's macro-economic performance and urged
the country to make greater efforts to ensure development pace,
Daily News said today.
</P>
<P>
"Tanzania is doing well... it has managed to bring down
inflation, interest rates, and the government has stopped
borrowing from local banks," World Bank (WB) resident
representative to Tanzania Ron Brigish, said here over the
weekend.
</P>
<P>
Tanzania has managed to bring down inflation from 25.1 percent
in January 1996 to 15.8 percent by the end of October, according
to the central Bank of Tanzania (BoT).
</P>
<P>
Brigish said he is hopeful of a positive response to Tanzania
from the donors, especially on debt relief.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that the Tanzanian government is spending 37
percent of its revenue on debt servicing.
</P>
<P>
However, the WB representatve said there is still need for the
country to ensure improvement in the power and road sectors to
sustain economic growth.
</P>
<P>
Brigish also hailed Tanzania's political stability, saying it
makes donors willing to aid the east African country.  
</P>
</TEXT>
