<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 14 Sentenced to Death in November in Philippines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, December 8 (Xinhua) -- Fourteen persons were sentenced
to death for heinous crimes in November in the Philippines,
bringing to 514 the total number of convicts awaiting execution,
the Philippine News Agency reported today.
</P>
<P>
The report said 11 of the 14 were convicted of aggravated rape,
two of murder and one of robbery with homicide.
</P>
<P>
Senator Ernesto Herrera, an anti-crime crusader and chief
advocate of the death penalty, said that among those sentenced to
death by lethal injection were eight fathers who raped their
daughters aged 9 to 17.
</P>
<P>
The Philippines resumed death penalty in 1995, but no one was
yet executed.
</P>
<P>
In light of the rampage of kidnapping-for-ransom cases, Herrera
appealed to the Supreme Court for expeditious review of such cases
"so that the executions may be carried out without further delay."
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, he prodded the Department of Justice to speed up the
prosecution of accused kidnappers, especially those facing the
death penalty. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
