<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Least Developing Countries Should Use Technical </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, December 8 (Xinhua) -- Bangladesh has called for finding
ways to break out of technological trap of transferring natural
resources at low prices in crude form from least developed
countries (LDCs) to advanced economies with a much higher value
addition, the independent United News of Bangladesh (UNB) reported
today.
</P>
<P>
"The LDCs could use technical assistance to learn to diversify
their products so that their share of the final price can
increase," Bangladesh Minister of Commerce and Industries Tofail
Ahmed said at the 7th UNIDO conference which began in Vienna
Monday, UNB quoted the message received in Dhaka as saying.
</P>
<P>
There is no alternative to industrialization for "it is only
through this that can we activize our dormant resources both
natural and human and attempt to energize our teaming millions
towards meaningful productive activity," the minister told the
conference.
</P>
<P>
The minister mentioned the LDCs' recommendations urging the
international community to initiate appropriate supportive
measures for enhancement of UNIDO's role as the specialized UN
agency for accelerating the industrialization process in the LDCs.
</P>
<P>
"In the foreseeable future, I see little prospect of LDCs being
able to make a breakthrough in the modernization process," he
said.
</P>
<P>
"Fast growing fields, such as finance, information and
biotechnology hold no hope for us in the short and medium terms,"
he stated. "Technological gap in these areas between LDCs and the
advanced countries are far too large."
</P>
<P>
Referring to barriers of entry of LDCs' outputs into the
developed markets, the minister said the benefits of
liberalization, which were expected to flow from the Uruguay Round
Agreement for all signatories, have often been eliminated by
raising new issues in the name of core labor standards,
environmental protection and even human rights.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
