<HEADLINE> Philippines' Exports Up 23.1 Percent in 10 Month </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, December 8 (Xinhua) -- The Philippines' export value
grew by 23.1 percent in the first 10 months of this year due to
the rapid growth of the country's exports of electronics, the
National Statistics Office said here today.
</P>
<P>
In a press statement, the office said: "Value of exports for
the first 10 months of 1997 grew by 23.1 percent to 20.687 billion
dollars, an increase of 3.878 billion dollars from 16.809 billion
dollars recorded in the previous year."
</P>
<P>
Dollar receipts from merchandise exports for October alone grew
by 23.4 percent to 2.324 billion dollars from 1.884 billion
dollars last year, it said.
</P>
<P>
Monthly growth rate dropped by 0.6 percent from 2.337 billion
dollars, the office said.
</P>
<P>
The office attributed the fast growth rate of this year to the
rise in exports of electronics and components, which represented
over 45 percent of the nation's total exports.
</P>
<P>
"Electronics and components were the country's consistent top
dollar earner for October 1997, which posted a 39.1 percent growth
to 1.086 billion dollars from 780.59 million dollars in October
1996," it said.
</P>
<P>
This commodity group accounted for 46.7 percent of the total
exports for October, the office said.
</P>
<P>
The United States, Japan and the Netherlands are the major
importers of the Philippine commodities. 
</P>
</TEXT>
