<BODY>
<HEADLINE> India Formulates New Reforms on Banking Sector </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, December 8 (Xinhua) -- The Reserve Bank of India
(RBI) has recommended alliances and joint ventures between private
and public sector banks to improve the profitability as well as
accountability of the latter, the local press said today.
</P>
<P>
The central bank in its latest report on "Trend and Progress of
Banking in India" has sought such operational freedom as part of
the second phase of banking sector reforms.
</P>
<P>
"Strategic alliances and cooperation would give banks a
competitive edge over other banks and financial intermediaries,"
the report said.
</P>
<P>
Public sector banks will have to acquire more expertise in
pricing of various risks to enable themselves to manage and modify
such exposures, the report said.
</P>
<P>
This can be done through greater managerial and operational
autonomy in strategic alliances with private sector banks, it
added.
</P>
<P>
The report, however, cautioned against overlapping of services
offered by banks, financial institutions and non-banking financial
companies which could lead to asset-liability mismatches.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971208.0204 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Minority Staff in U.S. Senate Get Less Pay Than White </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 7 (Xinhua) -- Minority staff members in
the U.S. Senate get less pay than their white counterparts, said a
congressional study released Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The average pay for black staff members dropped in 1997 -- 76
cents for every dollar earned by their white counterparts,
compared with 83 cents per every dollar in 1993, a report by the
Congressional Management Foundation, a nonpartisan group funded by
corporations, said.
</P>
<P>
The average pay for Hispanic staff workers increased this year,
but was still considerably lower than white members. Hispanics
earned 85 cents for every dollar in 1997, compared with 75 cents
per dollar in 1993.
</P>
<P>
Asians and Native Americans, who were grouped collectively in
the report, made up less than 2.8 percent of minority staff
members who worked in the Senate. They made 93 cents for every
dollar earned by white workers.
</P>
<P>
The study attributed the pay disparity to an overrepresentation
of minorities in lower paying jobs and an underrepresentation in
positions that were paid more.
</P>
<P>
Ethnic minorities comprise 13.6 percent of Senate staff, but
they hold only 4.6 percent of the five top-paying positions in
Senate personal offices, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The report emphasized that the salary disparities do not
reflect a different pay scale for employees who have similar
experiences and qualifications -- even if they are of different
races. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
