<DOCNO> XIE19971208.0207 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yearender: 1997, Year of Cooperation for ASEAN (4) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The ASEAN economic ministers meeting succeeded in moving the
ASEAN process of economic cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Other notable events in the year for ASEAN included the haze
which resulted from forest fires in Sumatera and Kalimantan in
Indonesia and blanketed parts of the region including Malaysia,
Singapore and Brunei for the last few months, affecting tourism
and other economic activities in these countries.
</P>
<P>
Of course, all the ASEAN countries are now completely free from
the haze and the ASEAN National Tourism Organizations have
launched a series of post-haze initiatives to stimulate tourist
arrivals to Southeast Asia.
</P>
<P>
Facing the currency and environmental problems, all the ASEAN
members realized more clearly the importance of closer cooperation
among themselves.
</P>
<P>
The members practiced the concept of "constructive engagement"
even though they adhere to the policy of non-interference in each
other's affairs.
</P>
<P>
As Malaysian Foreign Minister Abdullah Ahmad Badawi pointed
out, close cooperation among the ASEAN countries does not permit
them to isolate themselves or ignore each other's problems.
</P>
<P>
It was noted that in tackling regional issues, there has been a
tendency among the ASEAN members to help each other, showing the
grouping's unity.
</P>
<P>
To help Indonesia overcome its economic difficulties, Malaysia,
Singapore and Brunei pledged financial assistance.
</P>
<P>
To deal with the regional haze, Malaysia sent more than 1,000
firefighters to Indonesia to help put out the forest fires.
</P>
<P>
Local economists and analysts said the recent setbacks must be
viewed as temporary and transient, given the general resilience of
the ASEAN region.
</P>
<P>
As Malaysian Prime Minister Mahathir Mohamad put it, ASEAN has
emerged as one of the most cohesive regional groupings in the
world.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971208.0208 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yearender: 1997, Year of Cooperation for ASEAN (3) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
More Importantly, the speculative attacks on the region's
currencies have shown individual ASEAN countries that they cannot
isolate themselves from their neighbors, illustrating the
increased economic interdependence in the region and the mutual
interest in maintaining financial stability.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, the region's currency crisis prompted ASEAN to
decide to speed up economic cooperation, a necessity in the era of
globalization, by increasing regional trade and investment through
the realization of ASEAN Free Trade Area (AFTA) by the year 2003
as scheduled or earlier.
</P>
<P>
At the 11th AFTA council meeting held here on October 15, ASEAN
economic ministers agreed that the recent currency fluctuations in
the region have made the implementation of the AFTA an even more
important ASEAN economic cooperation activity.
</P>
<P>
Reviewing progress in the implementation of the Common
Effective Preferential Tariff (CEPT), the main operating mechanism
for AFTA, the ASEAN economic ministers agreed to speed up the
schedule and tariffs cuts for the AFTA.
</P>
<P>
Work on the proposed ASEAN Investment Area (AIA) which seeks to
promote ASEAN as a "single investment region" is also progressing
well.
</P>
<P>
The economic ministers shared the view that the implementation
of AFTA would facilitate long-term adjustments of their economies
to enhance ASEAN's resilience towards external volatility, and
they further expressed optimism on the long-term economic
prospects of the region as well as its attractiveness to foreign
investors.
</P>
<P>
To accelerate the achievement of the AFTA, they endorsed at
their 29th annual meeting here on October 16-17 several agreements
for liberalizing trade.
</P>
<P>
They approved the protocol on the Notification Procedure (NP),
expected to be signed early next year, which requires member
countries to inform each other at least 60 days in advance of any
modifications in their AFTA commitments, which might impair or
nullify any benefit of the CEPT scheme to members.
</P>
<P>
The economic ministers also endorsed the first package of
offers under the Framework Agreement on Services covering mainly
tourism, maritime and air transport services, which is scheduled
to be implemented simultaneously by all ASEAN members.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971208.0209 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yearender: 1997, Year of Cooperation for ASEAN (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The financial turmoil caused the currencies of these countries
to fall between 10 and 50 percent against the U.S. dollar and
their stock markets to plunge into new lows since July.
</P>
<P>
The crisis has brought about inflationary pressures and a
potential slowdown in the region. In Indonesia, Malaysia, the
Philippines and Thailand, inflation in the second half of this
year was estimated to move higher, offsetting gains that each of
these economies made in reducing inflation in the first half of
the year.
</P>
<P>
According to a recently released report "ASEAN Macroeconomic
Outlook 1997-1998" by ASEAN Secretariat, the prolonged turmoil in
the region's currency markets can affect economic fundamentals and
the grouping's prospects in the short term and possibly medium
term.
</P>
<P>
To curb currency speculation and manipulation, Malaysia put
forth a proposal that currency trading be regulated, which has
been supported by all ASEAN members and accepted by other
groupings such as G-15 and APEC.
</P>
<P>
On December 1-2, ASEAN finance ministers and their counterparts
from China, Japan, South Korea, Australia, the United States and
the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region of China met here to
especially address the current economic situation in the region
and exchange views on the causes and extent of the currency crisis
and policy responses needed to restore stability in the region.
</P>
<P>
With respect to the financial crisis, they focused on three key
issues -- the importance of enhancing transparency in currency
trading, the need for developing prudential and disclosure
standards in the financial markets and recent initiatives towards
the establishment of a regional surveillance and financing
arrangement.
</P>
<P>
On December 1, the ASEAN finance ministers also agreed to form
a regional surveillance mechanism within ASEAN as a preventive
effort to avoid the emergence of risks that would precipitate a
crisis.
</P>
<P>
The financial crisis in the region on one hand has hit badly
these economies and on the other hand has also provided ASEAN
members with an opportunity to eliminate inherent weaknesses and
to strengthen the foundation of their economies, with most
affected members currently making adjustments to counter the
effects of the currency and equity market turbulence.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
