<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka's Proposed Port to Be South Asia's Cargo Hub: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, December 8 (Xinhua) -- A World Bank (WB) specialist
said that a proposed port at Hambantota, Southern province of Sri
Lanka, could become a major cargo hub in South Asia once
completed, according to the local press reports today.
</P>
<P>
Ismail Mobarak, a WB official who was in Sri Lanka recently,
was quoted by the reports as saying that the proposed port was a
viable project specially for transshipment, break-bulking and
entrepot services.
</P>
<P>
The cost for the first phase of the project is estimated at 400
million U.S. dollars. The reports said once the first phase is
completed, the port will be able to handle nearly 200 ships daily
for bunkering and other services.
</P>
<P>
Sri Lanka's two major ports, the Colombo and Galle ports, are
overcrowded by ships due to a lack of space, the reports said.
</P>
