<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hearing on TWA Flight 800 Crash to Open in Seattle </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, December 7 (Xinhua) -- A week-long hearing to
explore causes of the TWA Flight 800 accident will open on Monday
in Seattle, where Boeing is headquartered.
</P>
<P>
The possibility of a technological failure in the airplane, the
25-year-old Boeing 747-100, will dominate the hearing sponsored by
the U.S. National Transportation Safety Board (NTSB), the 30-year
old agency in charge of investigating all civil-aviation accidents
and major accidents involving railroads, ships, hazardous
materials and pipelines.
</P>
<P>
The Boeing 747 broke up two and half miles above the Atlantic
Ocean, 13 minutes after it took off from John F. Kennedy
International Airport on July, 1996.
</P>
<P>
In addition to representatives from Boeing and TWA, 95
relatives of the 230 crash victims as well as their lawyers will
attend the Seattle hearing. Also present will be representatives
from France, the destination of the flight, and 500 journalists
from about 100 news organizations around the world.
</P>
<P>
Criminal probe at the early stage of the 17 months'
investigation seemed promising. But it ended last month with the
FBI conclusion that for the time being, the explosion was neither
an act of terrorism nor the result of a military mistake.
</P>
<P>
Now a center-wing-tank explosion, ignited by an undermining
spark, seems to be the only remaining clue to solving the mystery.
</P>
<P>
How a spark could have been produced inside the tank, which was
designed by Boeing to keep out flame, is now the kernel of the
issue. The Seattle Times quoted a top NTSB official as saying that
there are so far neither surprises nor any key piece of evidence
which could well account for a cause.
</P>
<P>
An attorney representing families of the crash victims has
contended that the three pumps on the rear spar of the 747's
center wing tank were vulnerable to malfunctions that could cause
fire, explosion or electrical arcing.
</P>
<P>
But the NTAB has virtually ruled out the pump as a cause for
lack of evidence in the Flight 800 wreckage of fire and tests had
shown that explosions inside the pumps did not lead to a blast
that could penetrate the pump housing and enter the fuel tank.
</P>
<P>
What is left is electricity inside the tanks. The 747's
fuel-quantity indicating system uses low-voltage current and metal
probes to measure fuel. In the event of a short circuit, Boeing
engineers say, the current could not ignite a spark sufficient to
cause fuel vapors. But if high-voltage current was somehow
introduced into the low-energy fuel-system circuit, a spark
sufficient to ignite the fumes was likely to occur.
</P>
<P>
Thus, how high-energy current could find its way into the tank
seems to be NTSB's current focus of investigation. But Boeing said
laboratory testing against the hypothesis has failed to prove it
as a realistic cause of the accident, and more tests remain to be
done.
</P>
<P>
So far, more than 100 suits have been filed against Boeing. A
lawyer for a victim's family said an explosive situation did exist
and that was a good product-liability case against Boeing. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971208.0214 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-08 </DATE_TIME>
