<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Asian Retreat From U.S. Financial Industry Predicted </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, December 7 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Analysts have
predicted a major Asian retreat from the U.S. financial industry
after Japan's Sumitomo Bank Ltd. said it was seeking to sell its
California Banks.
</P>
<P>
Asian Wall Street Journal reported Friday that Sumitomo Bank
has commissioned U.S. investment bank Goldman Sachs &AMP; Amp Co. to
find a buyer for its California unit, Sumitomo Bank of
California. It also said Goldman has approached several California
banks to see whether they were interested in an acquisition.
</P>
<P>
Sumitomo's action is just the beginning, said Kelvin Lee, a
director at the accounting and consulting firm Deloitte &AMP; Touche.
</P>
<P>
"Once you see Sumitomo find a buyer and if the price is
reasonable, you may see other people follow suit."
</P>
<P>
Hobbled by the crisis at home and burdened with hundreds of
billions of dollars in soured loans, Asian banks, such as
Sumitomo, are looking for ways to support their financial health,
analysts said, adding that one of the ways is shedding some or all
of their U.S. operations.
</P>
<P>
"This is a big reversal of strategy," said analyst Ricardo
Kleinbaum of Paine Webber in New York. He was referring to the
fact that the Asian financial institutions, during the past decade,
briskly expanded into the U.S. banking and real estate markets,
often using California as a beachhead.
</P>
<P>
Sumitomo Bank of California, which has 47 branches and 5.2
billion U.S. dollars in assets, makes it the six-largest bank in
the state, according to the California Bankers Association.
</P>
<P>
Some analysts had feared that Japanese banks might try to raise
capital by selling their vast holdings of U.S. Treasury bonds,
which could push U.S. interest rates higher. But others said
Sumitomo's action appeared to be an alternative that others might
follow.
</P>
<P>
There is another compelling reason for Sumitomo and the others
to consider selling their U.S. assets -- it is a seller's market
right now. The merger wave engulfing U.S. banking has placed
premium prices on banks that come up for sale. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971208.0216 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-08 </DATE_TIME>
