<HEADLINE> 5 Phones for Every 100 People in Sri Lanka by 2000 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, December 8 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lanka is aiming to achieve
a target of 5 telephones per 100 people by the year 2000, the
local press reported here today.
</P>
<P>
In Sri Lanka, every 100 people have only 1.4 telephones today,
the reports quoted the Sri Lanka Telecom (SLT) as saying.
</P>
<P>
The state-owned SLT now has 270,500 lines in service. The
company predicts that there will be 700,000 people on the
telephone waiting list by the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
The SLT believes it will be able to support around 500,000
telephone customers once the ongoing Wireless Local Loop (WLL)
projects are completed.
</P>
<P>
If Sri Lanka is to achieve the target of 5 telephones for every
100 people, another 300,000 lines should be provided, according to
the reports.
</P>
<P>
Sources in telecommunications circles said that in addition to
the investment already made, Sri Lanka needs about 500 million
U.S. dollars to fulfill the target.
</P>
<P>
In order to accelerate the pace, the country is exploring ways
for private companies to participate in telecommunications
infrastructure development endeavors.  
</P>
</TEXT>
