<HEADLINE> Serbians Voting for Republican President </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, December 7 (Xinhua) -- Electorate in the Republic of
Serbia began to vote today to elect a new president of the
republic to replace Slebodan Milosevic, who became federal
president of Yugoslavia in July.
</P>
<P>
The three main candidates are Foreign Minister Milan
Milutinovic, representing President Milosevic's ruling Socialist
Party (SPS), Radical Party (SRS) leader Vejislev Seselj and Vuk
Draskovic of the Serbian Renewal Movement.
</P>
<P>
The poll today follows the elections in October which failed
when none of the candidates got more than half of the votes.
</P>
<P>
In October, Seselj, a hardline nationalist, won the biggest
share of the vote in a run-off against Socialist candidate Zoren
Lilic.
</P>
<P>
An opinion poll in November by Ipress said 36 percent of the
electorate would be given to Milutinovic, 34 percent for Seselj
and 15 percent for Draskovic.
</P>
<P>
There is a saying here that the election today might also be
invalidated because of voter apathy and a low-key campaign.
</P>
<P>
If no one of the three candidates gets an overall majority in
today's re-run, a run-off between the top two candidates will be
held, probably on December 21. 
</P>
</TEXT>
