<HEADLINE> Tamil Party Wants Polls to Be Postponed in Northern </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, December 8 (Xinhua) -- The Tamil United Liberation
Front (TULF) urged the government to postpone the local government
elections in the north on the ground that the current situation in
the region does not ensure a free and fair election.
</P>
<P>
The local press said here today that the party urged the
government not to hold elections in Velanai, Kayts and Delft in
the north, which are controlled by an armed group that is
interested in contesting the polls.
</P>
<P>
The TULF, Sri Lanka's biggest Tamil party that holds five
parliament seats, also pointed out that displaced persons,
particularly the Muslims, have not been able to resettle in their
hometowns. Besides, people within the Jaffna district cannot move
freely due to various restrictions.
</P>
<P>
The party urged all parties in the north, which have armed
groups, to be disarmed prior to the elections.
</P>
<P>
Many other Tamil parties have also expressed their reservations
on the coming polls.
</P>
<P>
Nominations for general elections to municipal, urban and
village councils in Jaffna and Kilinochchi districts in the north
are to be received from December 16 to 23.
</P>
<P>
Sri Lanka held its local elections in all but Northern province
and parts of Eastern province in March this year. The polls had
been scheduled for 1995 but were postponed twice for security
reasons.
</P>
<P>
A 14-year-long civil war is going on between government troops
and the Tamil rebels in the north and east of the country.
</P>
<P>
Nominations were called at a time when troops of Operation
Jayasikuru (Certain Victory) are advancing further north through
rebel-held territories in their final phase of offensives.
</P>
</TEXT>
