<HEADLINE> Fifty Billion Roubles to Help Air Crash Sufferers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, December 7 (Xinhua) -- Russia has decided to allocate
50 billion roubles (about 8.62 million U.S. dollars) to help the
suffering residents in the Siberian city of Irkutsk, where a plane
crash took place on Saturday, killing more than 47 people.
</P>
<P>
A governmental decree made by Prime Minister Vikto
Chernomyridin, who arrived in Irkutsk to head the investigation of
the crash, said the money will be used mainly by the sufferers to
rebuild their homes.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, President Boris Yeltsin said in a statement, "I
expected the government to carry out a prompt investigation of the
causes of the tragedy and find those responsible."
</P>
<P>
The crash took place at about 2 p.m. local time Saturday, when
an Antonov-124, a huge Russian military cargo jet, plunged to the
ground seconds after taking off, plowing into four apartment
buildings, an orphanage and a school.
</P>
<P>
The victims included 23 people aboard the plane, two orphans in
the orphanage and 22 local residents. The death toll is reportedly
expected to rise as the rescue work goes on.
</P>
<P>
About 450 people have been evacuated from the area and the
rescue workers were continuing to search the debris and nearby
homes, 23 people were reportedly missing up to now.
</P>
<P>
Irkutsk experienced a crash in 1994 when all 125 people on
board a Russian Tupolev-154 plane were killed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
