<HEADLINE> China Wins Two Titles at French Open Table Tennis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, December 7 (Xinhua) -- Cheng Hongxia clinched two titles
for China as she won the singles first and then the doubles in the
French Open table tennis tournament in Lyons, France, on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The 19-year-old captured the women's singles by beating
compatriot Sun Jin 21-14, 16-21, 21-18, 21-17. The third place was
shared by Wang Hui of China and Jingtian Zorner of Germany.
</P>
<P>
The newly crowned Cheng, teamed-up with Wang Hui, carried her
winning streak into the doubles final where they downed French duo
of Anne Boileau and Anne Sophie Gourin 2-1.
</P>
<P>
Christophe Legout became the hero for the hosts after he routed
Danny Heister of the Netherlands in the men's singles final.
Legout upset tournament favorite Wang Liqin of China 3-2 in a
thrilling semifinal battle of 16-21, 21-18, 13-21, 21-19 and 21-11.
</P>
<P>
The third spot of men's singles was shared by Greek Kalinikos
Kreanga and Wang Liqin.
</P>
<P>
"The French Open is one of the major events in the world and
most of the players here are very close in their competing
levels." Cai Zhenhua, Chinese head coach, told a post game press
conference.
</P>
<P>
"China fielded a young line-ups here and they've tried their
best, especially the girls paddlers. However, they are still
lacking in international experience." Cai added.
</P>
<P>
French Open is the season ending leg of the series events held
by the International Table Tennis Federation (ITTF). According to
the overall standings, the top 16 singles players and top eight
duo will take part in the ITTF Grand Finales slated in Hong Kong
from December 18 to 21. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
