<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Regulates Publishing of National Standards </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 8 (Xinhua) -- China has drafted a set of
rules on improving official administration and coping with the
problem of greater piracy in the publication or duplication of
national standards.
</P>
<P>
The rules stipulate that the Standards Press of China has the
exclusive right to publish national standards. Departments under
the State Council and local governments in charge of drafting
sector and local standards are authorized to designate publishing
houses that should be responsible for the publication of relevant
sector and local standards.
</P>
<P>
The State Bureau of Technical Supervision (SBTS), which
monitors drafting and use of standards in China, has teamed up
with the State Press and Publication Administration to work out
the rules, according to today's China Daily.
</P>
<P>
The rules stipulate that the Standards Press of China is the
only publishing house entitled to publish and issue formal
international documents including ISO/IEC (International Standards
Organization/International Electrotechnical Commission) standards
and technical reports, translated or recognized by the SBTS as
authorized by ISO/IEC.
</P>
<P>
Any unit or individual wishing to issue standards for
profit-making motives will have to obtain written agreement in
advance from publishing houses with exclusive publication rights
before reproducing any part of the standard in any form.
</P>
<P>
Publishing houses which plan the publication of collections of
standards are also required to obtain written agreements in
advance from publishing houses with exclusive rights.
</P>
<P>
Any publication activities without official approval will be
punished. Those infringing the legal rights of standards
publishing houses will have civil responsibility.
</P>
<P>
The SBTS statistics showed that China has issued 17,720
national standards, 22,000 sector standards, and 8,000 local
standards by the end of 1996.
</P>
<P>
"China is protecting the intellectual property rights of
international standards in line with international agreements,"
said an SBTS official. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971208.0228 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Psychological Education Expands in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 8 (Xinhua) -- In China, teachers and parents
used to think that a good, healthy student simply means a strong
body and high scores in exams. The times are changing.
</P>
<P>
More and more college students today have come to realise that
healthy emotions and personalities are important for their lives
and studies.
</P>
<P>
Apart from academic subjects, college students are showing an
increasing interest in moral and psychological education,
according to the National Psychological Counselling Committee for
College Students, a non-government organization focusing on
promoting psychological education among college and universities
in China.
</P>
<P>
About 30 percent of the country's 1,032 colleges and
universities have set up psychological counselling centers.
</P>
<P>
According to the State Education Commission (SEC), moral
education has long been taught in primary and middle schools, and
colleges and universities in China.
</P>
<P>
And 70 percent of colleges and universities in Beijing and
Shanghai and all those in Dalian have opened psychological
counselling services to students.
</P>
<P>
However, in other areas, such as northwest China's Xinjiang
Uygur Autonomous Region, no school has yet introduced
psychological education. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
