<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Feature: Hong Kong Is My Home (by Tao Wenge) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, December 8 (Xinhua) -- Kevin Sinclair, a New
Zealand-born freelance journalist, was wild with joy when he
received his permanent identity card (ID card) of the Hong Kong
Special Administrative Region of China on November 18.
</P>
<P>
"I have waited for it for 30 years and now I am a Hong Konger,
not a foreigner," said Sinclair, 55, who came to Hong Kong in 1968
with a dream to seek a new and better life after working for 10
years in New Zealand, Australia and Southeast Asia for the press.
</P>
<P>
"My wife and I could never get permanent residence of Hong Kong
before, because neither of us are British," said Sinclair in an
exclusive interview with Xinhua at his home office with furniture
of ancient Chinese style and Chinese paintings and collections.
</P>
<P>
"So, to me, that is a big change for the better after the
Chinese government resumed its sovereignty over Hong Kong on July
1," Sinclair said.
</P>
<P>
"But in most ways, life has not changed. Everything works the
way it worked before, transport, shopping, education," he added.
</P>
<P>
Sinclair began his career in Wellington, New Zealand, as a copy
boy and promoted to a cadet reporter, a junior reporter, a
reporter and a chief reporter in the following years.
</P>
<P>
In Hong Kong, Sinclair continued his career as a journalist and
four years later became a columnist for South China Morning Post,
one of the major English newspapers in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
Since 1986, he has worked as a freelance journalist. Everyday
he spends long hours working at his computer, and every week he
gets his articles printed in local English newspapers and overseas
publications.
</P>
<P>
Sinclair writes for the Asia Magazine, the largest English
circulation in Asia, the Sunday Express in London, Business Travel
International and other newspapers and magazines.
</P>
<P>
He has published 12 books on Hong Kong and China, which include
"Asia's Finest," "A History of the Royal Hong Kong Police," "The
Yellow River: a 5,000 year journey through China" and "Over China:
geographical overview of the nation."
</P>
<P>
His articles are mainly about the current affairs of Hong Kong
and China as a whole. Asked which of his articles he likes most,
Sinclair said he doesn't know but he is keen to tell the truth of
Hong Kong and China as a whole.
</P>
<P>
Sinclair and his wife, Kit Allred, a professor at the Hong Kong
Polytechnic University, have been visiting China's mainland provinces
regularly.
</P>
<P>
Talking about the future, Sinclair said the social outlook for
Hong Kong is good because SAR Chief Executive Tung Chee Hwa and
his colleagues are determined to make life better for the average
people.
</P>
<P>
"We have a marvelous team in our government and civil service,
all of them are dedicated to making sure Hong Kong remains a
wonderful place to live in," Sinclair said.
</P>
<P>
"The stress on a better housing policy is something that our
society needs. We also need to remain an international city and
here is one area that I do not think Tung has done enough to
express himself," Sinclair said.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong's social development depends solely on its sound and
strong economic development, as it always has, he said. "I think
Tung knows this," he added.
</P>
<P>
"If we do not have a good economy, we can not have social
improvements. What's good for the average person is good for our
community," Sinclair continued.
</P>
<P>
As for the recent financial turmoil in Asia and the stock
market volatility in Hong Kong, Sinclair said that he feels that
Tung and Donald Tsang, the secretary for finance, have done a very
good job in controlling forces which are mostly out of their
control.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong alone can not stop international markets from falling
and if Tokyo and Wall Street and other markets fall, then so will
the Hong Kong market. That is inevitable, Sinclair said.
</P>
<P>
But the determination and efficiency with which they have shown
they will keep the peg with the U.S. dollar has been very
effective in stopping Hong Kong's economy from suffering more.
</P>
<P>
"I think they have done a very good job so far. Let's hope this
can continue," Sinclair said. "Naturally, as a Hong Konger, I
support what they are doing," he added.
</P>
<P>
"I love Hong Kong because this is my home. It's the best place
to live in. I don't think someday Hong Kong might become a place
where I can not live comfortably. Hong Kong gets a wonderful
future for me and my family," Sinclair said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
