<HEADLINE> Serbian Democrats Lose Ruling Position </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, December 7 (Xinhua) -- The Serbian Democratic Party,
though leading in the National Assembly election of the Republic
of Srpska November 22 to 23, has lost its ruling party position.
</P>
<P>
This was announced today by Rodzer Brajant, the European
Security and Cooperation Organization representative to Banja Luka.
</P>
<P>
Brajant said the Democrat Party pulled 24 out of the 83 seats
in the assembly. It was followed by the Bosnian League for
Integrity and Democracy with 16 seats; the Srpski Narodnisavez,
founded by President Biljana Plavsic in late August, and the
Serbian Radical Party, with 15 seats each; the Serbian Socialist
Party with 9 seats; and the Serbian Independent Socialist
Democratic Party and the Socialist Democratic Party with two seats
each.
</P>
<P>
Observants here say, despite its victory, the current election
has cost the Democratic Party its ruling position and thus ended
its dominance in the assembly. However, they believe the election
result was not likely to overcome the present political crisis in
view of the fact that the Bosnian Serb Republic has actually been
separated into two regimes in the east and west. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
