<DOCNO> XIE19971208.0243 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yearender: Peace Remains Distant Dream in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, December 8 (Xinhua) -- The year 1997 is approaching
its end, yet for the war-weary Afghans peace remains a distant
dream.
</P>
<P>
The Afghan civil war, which has been protracted for nearly 18
years, is in no way dying out as rigid warring factions are
reluctant to bury their hatchets.
</P>
<P>
The lingering conflict has witnessed perhaps the most dramatic
changes on the war front this year as the Islamic Taliban militia
and rival northern alliance were engaged in the see-saw fighting
time and again.
</P>
<P>
The Taliban, who control about two-thirds of the Afghan
territory and the capital of Kabul, remain the dominant force in
the country though they have failed in several attempts to seize
northern Afghanistan controlled by the northern alliance.
</P>
<P>
The anti-Taliban alliance, based in Mazar-e-Sharif, around 300
km north of Kabul, is composed of forces led by Uzbek warlord
Rashid Dostum, former Afghan military chief Ahmad Masood and the
Shiite Hezb-e-Wadhat.
</P>
<P>
The two sides had been locked in a stalemate for about 5 months
since January when the Taliban pushed in a blitz the northern
alliance forces from 20 km north of Kabul to 150 km.
</P>
<P>
The situation took a dramatic turn in mid-May when Uzbek
warlord Abdul Malik, Dostum's right-hand man, suddenly mutinied
against him and sided with the Taliban, enabling the hard-line
militia to make a breakthrough in the opposition-held north.
</P>
<P>
Buoyed by their landmark victory, the Taliban, who vowed to
impose a strict Islamic rule in Afghanistan, entered on May 25
Mazar-e-Sharif, Afghanistan's second largest city, and even
claimed they would complete "in days" their three-year campaign to
take over the whole country.
</P>
<P>
A few days later, however, Malik unexpectedly broke rank with
the Taliban and rejoined the northern alliance, forcing the
Taliban to retreat from the newly-captured northern areas.
</P>
<P>
Malik's about-face led to the Taliban's worst defeat after
their rise from southern Afghanistan in 1994. It also provided an
opportunity for Masood, who had been biding his time in Panjshir
valley, about 150 km north of Kabul, to launch a strong offensive
against the Taliban in early July.
</P>
<P>
In less than two weeks, Masood's forces advanced to within 20
km north of Kabul, putting the city within the striking range of
Masood's rockets. So far the Taliban have failed to force Masood's
men to retreat.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971208.0244 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yearender: Peace Remains Distant Dream in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The world may have given up Afghanistan as a hopeless case but
peace in Afghanistan is vital for the survival of its people and
for the economic progress and political stability of the entire
region.
</P>
<P>
As the Afghan war continued to rage, the United Nations has
never stopped its efforts this year to bring rapprochement among
the warring factions but has failed to make any headway.
</P>
<P>
U.N. Special Envoy to Afghanistan Norber Holl attributed this
failure to "internal and external factors which were not ready for
peace in the country."
</P>
<P>
"The internal factor is that there was not sufficient sense of
compromise among all Afghan parties and secondly the country with
influence has not yet in the past seriously discussed with the
U.N. the way to get out of the Afghanistan dilemma," Holl said in
a recent interview with Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
The German diplomat, who resigned from his U.N. post recently,
said the U.N. has been focusing its attention on mediating between
the Afghans during the past five years, but the lack of comprise
among all Afghan parties has rendered this method fruitless.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, he added, the U.N. is considering changing its
strategy in brokering peace in Afghanistan by shifting the focus
from the Afghan warring factions to the regional countries with
influence upon the country.
</P>
<P>
The developments of the Afghan situation this year once again
proved that the country's lingering conflict could not be solved
militarily.
</P>
<P>
It is evident that Afghanistan, a country composed of
multi-ethnic groups, cannot function smoothly under the complete
domination of one particular group even though it might be
militarily the strongest.
</P>
<P>
Observers here believe that given the deep divisions among the
Afghan warring factions on political, ethnic, ideological and
tribal lines, permanent peace, which has eluded Afghanistan for a
long period, will not return to the country in the absence of a
broad-based government representing interests of all the groups.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
