<DOCNO> XIE19971208.0253 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkey Opposes Cyprus' Accession Talks With EU </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, December 7 (Xinhua) -- Turkish Prime Minister Mesut
Yilmaz said here today that Turkey firmly opposes the upcoming
accession talks between the Cypriot government and the European
Union (EU).
</P>
<P>
The Greek Cypriot-dominated government has no right to seek EU
membership on behalf of the whole island, Yilmaz said in a meeting
with a Turkish Cypriot delegation, the Anatolia News Agency
reported.
</P>
<P>
He said the Turkish Cypriot community should also be
represented in the delegation for the negotiations as an equal
partner.
</P>
<P>
"No other formula could make Turkish Cypriots attend the
upcoming negotiations," he was quoted by the news agency as saying.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus, an eastern Mediterranean island, submitted in 1990 its
application for full membership to the European Union, which has
decided to start the negotiations early next year.
</P>
<P>
EU's decision angered the Turkish Cypriots as well as Turkey
which also has applied for EU membership, but excluded in the
process of enlargement of the European bloc.
</P>
<P>
Turkey and Turkish Cypriots signed in August an agreement on
partial integration in protest against EU's decision.
</P>
<P>
Yilmaz said that Turkey has made its position clear in various
contacts with EU leaders, adding that it is the EU that should
make a wise decision now.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided since 1974 when Turkish troops landed
on the island and took over the northern third following an
abortive coup by the Greek Cypriots seeking union with Greece.
</P>
<P>
Turkish Cypriots declared unilaterally in 1983 a breakaway
"Turkish Republic of Northern Cyprus," which is only recognized by
Ankara. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
