<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lower Alcohol Limit Won't Cut Road Death: Study </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, December 7 (Xinhua) -- A New study suggested that a
lower alcohol limit will have no long-term effect on road accident
rates, which is at odds with British government plans to introduce
tougher drink-driving laws, said local press reports today.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that the UK government is planning to reduce
the permitted alcohol limit from 80 milligrams of alcohol per 100
milliliters of blood to 50 milligrams.
</P>
<P>
However, the study by the British Institute of Traffic
Education Research said that the main problem lies with heavier
drinkers who habitually break existing limits and thus a 50 mg
limit offers little help.
</P>
<P>
The study showed that there are 1.5 road deaths for every
10,000 vehicles in Britain, compared with three per 10,000
vehicles in France, which has a 50 mg limit. In the Netherlands,
where the limit is 22 mg, there are 1.8 deaths per 10,000
vehicles.
</P>
<P>
The study, which is funded by several drinks companies,
proposed instead measures such as devices to disable cars if the
driver is over the limit and also harsher sentences alongside
rehabilitation programs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
