<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-07 21:45 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Progress in Guerrilla-Israeli Negotiations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, December 7 (Xinhua) -- The Islamic resistance force in
South Lebanon Hezbollah today called for more progress in
negotiations with Israelis for exchange the remains of an Israeli
soldier for Lebanese prisoners.
</P>
<P>
Progress has been made in the negotiations, but the
developments are "not enough," Secretary General Sheikh Hassan
Nasrallah of the Hezbollah, or Party of God, said in an interview
with the radio Voice of People, a mouthpiece of the Lebanese
Communist Party.
</P>
<P>
He ruled out possibility to hold more talks in the coming days.
</P>
<P>
The Hezbollah is negotiating with Israel, under the auspices of
the International Committee of the Red Cross, for exchanging the
remains of an Israeli soldier killed in a raid in south Lebanon
last September for Lebanese prisoners held in the Jewish state.
</P>
<P>
The two sides currently have been bargaining how many Lebanese
prisoners should be freed. At the next stage, they would determine
who should be released.
</P>
<P>
Hezbollah is leading a guerrilla war in South Lebanon to oust
Israeli troops from the 1,100-square-kilometer security which was
set up by Israel in 1985 to prevent cross-border attacks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
